{"title_page": "Richard Horton (editor)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Richard Horton (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Richard Horton\n| native_name = Richard Charles Horton\n| native_name_lang = \n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRCP|FMedSci|size=100}}\n| image       =   Dr. Richard Horton, Editor in Chief, the Lancet (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = Richard Horton in 2013\n| birth_date  =   {{birth date and age|df=y|1961|12|29}}<ref name=whoswho/>\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  =   <!--{{death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|1961|12|29}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| residence   = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields      = \n| workplaces  = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[The Lancet]]''\n* [[Royal Free Hospital]]}}\n| patrons     = \n| education   = [[Bristol Grammar School]]<ref name=whoswho/>\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Birmingham]] (BSc, MB ChB)\n| thesis_title =  <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =   <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =   <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = \n| spouse      =   {{marriage|Ingrid Johanna Wolfe|1988}}<ref name=whoswho/>\n| partner     =   <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children    = 1 daughter<ref name=whoswho/>\n| signature   =   <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =   {{URL|https://www.theguardian.com/profile/richardhorton}}\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Richard Charles Horton''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRCP|FMedSci}} (born 29 December 1961) is [[editor-in-chief]] of ''[[The Lancet]]'', a [[United Kingdom]]\u2013based [[medical journal]].<ref name=whoswho>{{Who's Who | author=Anon|surname = Horton | othernames = Dr Richard Charles | id = U20825 | year = 2014 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U20825}} </ref><ref name=scopus>{{Scopus|id=26643541300}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1001/jama.276.8.637| pmid = 8773637| title = Improving the quality of reporting of randomized controlled trials. The CONSORT statement| journal = JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association| volume = 276| issue = 8| pages = 637\u2013639| year = 1996| last1 = Begg | first1 = C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(11)60393-0| title = Priority actions for the non-communicable disease crisis| journal = The Lancet| volume = 377| issue = 9775| pages = 1438\u201347| year = 2011| last1 = Beaglehole | first1 = R. | last2 = Bonita | first2 = R. | last3 = Horton | first3 = R. | last4 = Adams | first4 = C. | last5 = Alleyne | first5 = G. | last6 = Asaria | first6 = P. | last7 = Baugh | first7 = V. | last8 = Bekedam | first8 = H. | last9 = Billo | first9 = N. | last10 = Casswell | first10 = S. | last11 = Cecchini | first11 = M. | last12 = Colagiuri | first12 = R. | last13 = Colagiuri | first13 = S. | last14 = Collins | first14 = T. | last15 = Ebrahim | first15 = S. | last16 = Engelgau | first16 = M. | last17 = Galea | first17 = G. | last18 = Gaziano | first18 = T. | last19 = Geneau | first19 = R. | last20 = Haines | first20 = A. | last21 = Hospedales | first21 = J. | last22 = Jha | first22 = P. | last23 = Keeling | first23 = A. | last24 = Leeder | first24 = S. | last25 = Lincoln | first25 = P. | last26 = McKee | first26 = M. | last27 = MacKay | first27 = J. | last28 = Magnusson | first28 = R. | last29 = Moodie | first29 = R. | last30 = Mwatsama | first30 = M. | display-authors = 29 | pmid=21474174}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(96)90137-3| pmid = 8606606| title = Surgical research or comic opera: Questions, but few answers| journal = The Lancet| volume = 347| issue = 9007| pages = 984\u2013985| year = 1996| last1 = Horton | first1 = R. }}</ref><ref name=youtube>{{YouTube|id=v7BzM5mxN5U Richard Horton speech at Time to Go anti-war demonstration in Manchester on 2006-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1001/jama.286.10.1232| pmid = 11559271| title = Sponsorship, Authorship, and Accountability| journal = JAMA| volume = 286| issue = 10| pages = 1232\u20134| year = 2001| last1 = Davidoff | first1 = F. | pmc = 81460}}</ref><ref name=moribund>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61050-3| title = Offline: The moribund body of medical history| journal = The Lancet| volume = 384| issue = 9940| pages = 292| year = 2014| last1 = Horton | first1 = R. }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nHorton studied at [[Bristol Grammar School]]<ref name=whoswho/> from 1969 to 1980 and at the [[University of Birmingham]] from 1980 to 1986, receiving his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in physiology in 1983, and his [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery]] degree 1986. He completed his general medical training in Birmingham before moving to the [[Royal Free Hospital]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1990, Horton joined ''[[The Lancet]]'' as an assistant editor and moved to New York as North American editor in 1993. Two years later he returned to the UK to become Editor-in-Chief.\n\nHorton served as a medical columnist for ''[[The Observer]]'' and writes for ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'' and ''[[The New York Review of Books]]''. His book about controversies in modern medicine, ''Second Opinion: Doctors, Diseases and Decisions in Modern Medicine'', was published in 2003. (In the United States, it was published under the title ''Health Wars: On the Global Front Lines of Modern Medicine''.)\n\nIn 2005 he was a member of the working party and subsequently wrote the report for the [[Royal College of Physicians]]' inquiry into the future of medical professionalism \u2013 \"Doctors in Society\" (2005). He also chaired the [[Royal College of Physicians]]' Working Party on Physicians and the Pharmaceutical Industry; co-chaired a [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) Scientific Advisory Group on Clinical Trials Registration;<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1056/NEJMe048225| title = Clinical Trial Registration: A Statement from the International Committee of Medical Journal Editors| journal = New England Journal of Medicine| volume = 351| issue = 12| pages = 1250\u20131| year = 2004| last1 = De Angelis | first1 = C. | last2 = Drazen | first2 = J. M. | last3 = Frizelle | first3 = F. A. | last4 = Haug | first4 = C. | last5 = Hoey | first5 = J. | last6 = Horton | first6 = R. | last7 = Kotzin | first7 = S. | last8 = Laine | first8 = C. | last9 = Marusic | first9 = A. | last10 = Overbeke | first10 = A. J. P. M. | last11 = Schroeder | first11 = T. V. | last12 = Sox | first12 = H. C. | last13 = Weyden | first13 = M. B. V. D. | pmid=15356289}}</ref> chaired the Board of the Health Metrics Network; sat on the External Reference Group for WHO's Research Strategy; and is an External Advisory Board Member for the WHO European Region.<ref name=abouthtelancet/> Currently, he co-chairs the independent Expert Review Group on Information and Accountability for Women's and Children' Health. He is also a Council member of both the Academy of Medical Sciences and the University of Birmingham.\n\nHorton was the first President of the World Association of Medical Editors, and is a Past-President of the US [[Council of Science Editors]] (2005\u201306). He is an honorary professor at the [[London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]], the [[University College London]], and the [[University of Oslo]]. He is a Fellow of both of the Royal College of Physicians and of the UK's [[Academy of Medical Sciences]].<ref name=abouthtelancet>{{cite web | url=http://www.thelancet.com/lancet-about | title=About the Lancet | publisher=[[The Lancet]] | accessdate=2013-09-03}}</ref> In 2011, he was elected to the US [[Institute of Medicine]].<ref name=pmc558552>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.331.7507.53 |pmc=558552 |year=2005 |last1=Watts |first1=G |title=A right royal spat |journal=BMJ : British Medical Journal |volume=331 |issue=7507 |pages=53 }}</ref><ref>\"IOM Elects 65 New Members, Five Foreign Associates\" (Press release). Institute of Medicine. 17 October 2011. Retrieved 6 January 2016.[http://iom.nationalacademies.org/Global/News%20Announcements/2011-New-Members.aspx Institute of Medicine website]</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Horton was appointed to a research and analytical management panel as a Senior Associate of The [[Nuffield Trust]], a major independent health policy institution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuffieldtrust.org.uk/media-centre/press-releases/nuffield-trust-rejuvenates|title=Media centre|date=31 January 2017|website=Nuffieldtrust.org.uk|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> In 2016, he was appointed by [[United Nations Secretary-General]] [[Ban Ki-moon]] to an expert group advising the High-Level Commission on Health Employment and Economic Growth, which was co-chaired by presidents [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] of [[France]] and [[Jacob Zuma]] of [[South Africa]].<ref>[http://www.who.int/hrh/com-heeg/hrh_heeg_bios/en/ High-Level Commission on Health Employment and Economic Growth \u2013 Expert Group] [[World Health Organization]].</ref> In 2017, he served on the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) /[[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] (UNHCR) High-Level Working Group on the Health and Human Rights of Women, Children and Adolescents, chaired by [[Tarja Halonen]] and [[Hina Jilani]].<ref>[http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/255540/1/9789241512459-eng.pdf Leading the realization of human rights to health and through health: Report of the High-Level Working Group on the Health and Human Rights of Women, Children and Adolescents (2017)] [[World Health Organization]].</ref>\n\n=== Climate change and health professionals ===\nA few days after the word-wide mobilisation promoted by the activist movement [[Extinction Rebellion]], Horton asserts in a video that health professionals should involve themselves directly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/life/1317926/video-lancet-editor-richard-horton-urges-medical-licensing-body-not-punish-doctors|title=Video: Lancet editor Richard Horton urges medical licensing body not to punish doctors in Extinction Rebellion protests|date=2019-10-25|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref> He started by saying:<ref>{{Citation|title=Health and Climate - Richard Horton, The Lancet|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2x6sBfV64N4|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref>\n\n{{Block quote|The climate emergency that we're facing today is the most important existential crisis facing the human species. And since medicine is all about protecting and strengthening the human species, it should be absolutely foundational to the practice of what we do every single day.\n\nThe [[General Medical Council|GMC]] [General Medical Council] published an extremely important document, which guides all health professionals, \"Duties of a doctor\". The duties of a doctor are first and foremost to an individual patient or to the public that they serve.\n\nThe climate crisis is one of the most, I would say ''the most'', existential crisis facing our communities in the world today. Doctors and all health professionals have a responsibility, an obligation, to engage in all kinds of non-violent social protests to address the climate emergency. That is the duty of a doctor. [...]}}\n\n===Denial of retraction of discredited vaccine paper===\n{{see also|The Lancet#Controversies}}\n\nOn 28 February 1998 Horton published a controversial paper by Dr [[Andrew Wakefield]] and 12 co-authors with the title \u201cIleal-lymphoid-nodular hyperplasia, non-specific colitis, and pervasive developmental disorder in children\" suggesting that vaccines could cause autism. The publication of the paper set off a sharp decline in vaccinations in Europe and America and in subsequent years globally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/03/health/research/03lancet.html|title=British Journal Retracts Paper Linking Autism and Vaccines|first=Gardiner|last=Harris|date=2 February 2010|accessdate=8 June 2018|website=Nytimes.com}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the Health Protection Agency attributed a large measles outbreak in 2008 and 2009 to a concurrent drop in the number of children receiving the MMR vaccine. Pockets of measles \u2014 which can be fatal \u2014have also cropped up in Canada and the United States as a result of parents\u2019 refusal to vaccinate.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Lancet retracts 12-year-old article linking autism to MMR vaccines|first=Laura|last=Eggertson|date=9 March 2010|journal=CMAJ|volume=182|issue=4|pages=E199\u2013E200|doi=10.1503/cmaj.109-3179|pmid=20142376|pmc=2831678}}</ref>\n\nHorton was heavily criticised for refusing to take action for so long. He was finally forced to retract the paper in February 2010 after the General Medical Council, which oversees doctors in Britain, said that \"there was a biased selection of patients in ''The Lancet'' paper\" and that Wakefield's \"conduct in this regard was dishonest and irresponsible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/HEALTH/02/02/lancet.retraction.autism/index.html|title=Medical journal retracts study linking autism to vaccine|website=Cnn.com|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Horton defended his position by saying \"I do not regret publishing the original Wakefield paper. Progress in medicine depends on the free expression of new ideas. I worked at the Royal Free from 1988 to 1990 and met him on many occasions. He is a committed, engaging, and charismatic clinician and scientist. He asks big questions about diseases - what are their ultimate causes? - and his ambition often brings quick and impressive results.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://briandeer.com/mmr/horton-wakefield.htm|title=Andrew Wakefield \u2013 the fraud investigation \u2013 Brian Deer|website=briandeer.com|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> However, there are groups criticising Horton for contributing to the ongoing dramatic drop of vaccination of children in Europe and America that causes several epidemics and deaths by delaying the retraction of the paper for 12 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-39419976|title=Measles outbreak across Europe|date=28 March 2017|accessdate=8 June 2018|website=Bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n===Royal Society===\nIn the 11 May 2005 ''The Lancet'', Horton criticized the ancient British scientific group, the [[Royal Society]], under [[Martin Rees|Lord Rees]] for its neglect of medicine.<ref name=pmc558552/> Professor Mark Pepys and thirty other society members responded. A few years earlier the society and the journal had taken different positions in a scientific reporting debate known as the [[Pusztai affair]] involving research on genetically modified potatoes.\n\n===Professor Sir Roy Meadow===\nHorton published an article in 2005 supporting Professor Sir [[Roy Meadow]] who had been charged with serious professional misconduct by the GMC for giving erroneous and seriously misleading evidence in the [[Sally Clark]] trial. This was especially controversial as the article appeared whilst the GMC proceedings were still under away and was published on the first day of Meadow's defence. The article \"incensed\" Clark, a solicitor who had been the victim of a serious miscarriage of justice. With the support of erroneous statistical (and other) evidence from Meadow the prosecution wrongly convicted her of murder and she spent over three years in prison before her successful second appeal.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)66798-0 |pmid=15993209 |title=In defence of Roy Meadow |journal=The Lancet |volume=366 |issue=9479 |pages=3\u20135 |year=2005 |last1=Horton |first1=Richard }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/4641587.stm|title=Cot death expert defends evidence|date=1 July 2005|accessdate=8 June 2018|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHer husband wrote a rebuttal letter to ''The Lancet'' in order to correct Horton's 'many inaccuracies and one-sided opinions' and to prevent them prejudicing independent observers. Dr [[James Le Fanu]], medical practitioner and writer, also wrote to ''The Lancet'' in the same issue and described Horton's words as 'mischief'.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)67048-1 |pmid=16084242 |title=Roy Meadow |journal=The Lancet |volume=366 |issue=9484 |pages=449\u2013450 |year=2005 |last1=Clark |first1=Stephen }}</ref> The Clark family issued a statement addressing and countering with established fact each of the points making up Horton's biased support of Meadow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sallyclark.org.uk/Lancet050701.html|title=Sally Clark: Statement to the Lancet 1.7.05|website=Sallyclark.org.uk|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Iraq===\n{{Main|Lancet surveys of Iraq War casualties|Casualties of the Iraq War}}\nAt the ''Time to Go Demo'' of 23 September 2006, Horton accused American president [[George W. Bush]] and British prime minister [[Tony Blair]] of \"lies\" and \"killing children\" in [[Iraq]].  On 11 October, ''The Lancet'' published new estimates of the death toll of Iraqi citizens after the US-led [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion in 2003]], putting it at a total of 655,000. Some supporters of the invasion of Iraq dismissed it for what they claimed was flawed methodology.<ref>{{cite news|title= Huge gaps in Iraq death estimates|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/6045112.stm|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=12 October 2006 | first=Paul | last=Reynolds}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Critics attack huge Iraqi casualty figures|url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/irq061012|publisher=[[Radio Netherlands]]|date=12 October 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061207153847/http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/irq061012|archivedate=7 December 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Lancet' back at centre of controversy|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article1842560.ece|publisher=The Independent|date=13 October 2006|location=London|first=Ben|last=Russell|accessdate=2010-05-22|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001313/http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article1842560.ece|archivedate=1 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some opponents of the invasion questioned its reliability due to its extreme divergence from other data on the conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iraqbodycount.org/press/pr14.php|title=Iraq Body Count Press Release 14 (16 Oct 2006) :: Iraq Body Count|website=Iraqbodycount.org|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Some journals and statistical experts were supportive. Other experts in the field were not convinced, saying the estimates were \"high, and probably way too high\",<ref>{{cite news | url=http://blog.washingtonpost.com/worldopinionroundup/2006/10/is_iraqs_civilian_death_toll_h.html | work=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=2010-05-22 | title=Is Iraq's Civilian Death Toll 'Horrible' -- Or Worse? | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011180035/http://blog.washingtonpost.com/worldopinionroundup/2006/10/is_iraqs_civilian_death_toll_h.html | archivedate=11 October 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and that the authors had published a \"misinterpretation of their own figures\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2007/01/28/2003346700 |title=The civilian death toll in Iraq war proves a nebulous statistic |last= Daponte |first=Beth Osborne |date=January 28, 2007 |website=[[Taipei Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303193139/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2007/01/28/2003346700 |archive-date= March 3, 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref> \nOthers were incredulous that the survey could have been performed as reported under such dangerous conditions.<ref name=iraqdeathtoll>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/443728a| title = Iraqi death toll withstands scrutiny| journal = Nature| year = 2006| last1 = Giles | first1 = J.| pmid=17051169| volume=443| issue = 7113| pages=728\u20139| doi-access = free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.314.5798.396| pmid = 17053114| title = Epidemiology: Iraqi Death Estimates Called Too High; Methods Faulted| journal = Science| volume = 314| issue = 5798| pages = 396\u20137| year = 2006| last1 = Bohannon | first1 = John| authorlink1 = John Bohannon}}</ref>\n\nIraq's health minister estimated during a press conference in November 2006 that between 100,000 and 150,000 people had died since the invasion in 2003, based on an estimate of around 100 deaths per day brought to morgues and hospitals during 2006,<ref>{{cite news|title=Iraq issues controversial death toll|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/08e4ce42-70dc-11db-8e0b-0000779e2340.html|work=[[Financial Times]]|date=10 November 2006}}</ref> while saying that the ''Lancet'' estimates were an \"exaggerated number\".<ref name=\"IHT\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/11/09/europe/EU_GEN_Austria_Iraqis_Killed.php |title=Iraqi health minister estimates as many as 150,000 Iraqis killed by insurgents |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |date=November 9, 2006 |website=[[International Herald Tribune]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918000905/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/11/09/europe/EU_GEN_Austria_Iraqis_Killed.php |archive-date=2008-09-18 |url-status=dead |access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\n===Open Letter for the People of Gaza===\n\nIn August 2014 ''The Lancet'' published An Open letter for the people of Gaza,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61044-8| pmid = 25064592| title = An open letter for the people in Gaza| journal = The Lancet| volume = 384| issue = 9941| pages = 397\u2013398| year = 2014| last1 = Manduca | first1 = P. | last2 = Chalmers | first2 = I. | last3 = Summerfield | first3 = D. | last4 = Gilbert | first4 = M. | last5 = Ang | first5 = S. }}</ref> criticising Israel in the wake of the [[2014 Gaza conflict]].\n\nHorton responded to criticism of the letter by saying that it was \"a [[smear campaign]]\" and that he didn't \"honestly see what all this has to do with the Gaza letter. I have no plans to retract the letter, and I would not retract the letter even if it was found to be substantiated\".<ref name= Lazareva/> However, Horton subsequently came to Israel's [[Rambam Hospital]] for a visit and said that he \"deeply, deeply regret[ted] the completely unnecessary polarization that publication of the letter by Paola Manduca caused\".<ref name= Lazareva>{{cite news | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author= Lazareva, Inna|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/israel/11137943/Lancet-editor-apologises-for-Gaza-article-by-scientists-who-promoted-Ku-Klux-Klan.html | title=Lancet editor apologises for Gaza article by scientists who promoted Ku Klux Klan | date=3 October 2014 | accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.618899 | work=[[Haaretz]]|title=In Israel, Lancet editor regrets publishing open letter on Gaza | date=3 October 2014 | accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Health/The-Lancet-editor-relents-on-medical-journals-unbalanced-attacks-on-Israel-377937 |author=Siegel-Itzkovich, Judy|work=[[Jerusalem Post]]|title=The Lancet editor relents on medical journal's unbalanced attacks on Israel | date=2 October 2014 | accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nProfessor Sir [[Mark Pepys]] wrote: \"The failure of the Menduca et al authors to disclose their extraordinary conflicts of interest\u2026 are the most serious, unprofessional and unethical errors. The transparent effort to conceal this vicious and substantially mendacious partisan political diatribe as an innocent humanitarian appeal has no place in any serious publication, let alone a professional medical journal, and would disgrace even the lowest of the gutter press.\" In addition, Pepys accused Horton personally saying that \"Horton\u2019s behavior in this case is consistent with his longstanding and wholly inappropriate use of ''The Lancet'' as a vehicle for his own extreme political views. It has greatly detracted from the former high standing of the journal.\" In response, Horton said: \"How can you separate politics and health? The two go hand-in-hand.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/11112930/Lancet-hijacked-in-anti-Israel-campaign.html | title=Lancet 'hijacked in anti-Israel campaign' | author= Wallis Simons, Jake |date=22 September 2014 | accessdate=2 October 2014|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus Pandemic===\n\nDr. Horton's initial response to the outbreak of [[Coronavirus]] was cautious, telling his Twitter followers on 23 January 2020 that Covid-19 probably \"has moderate transmissibility and relatively low pathogenicity.\" But, as evidence came in from China, on 29 January, he said: \"It must now surely be time to declare a Public Health Emergency of International Concern.\" And, on 31 January, he tweeted about \"draconian measures that limit population mobility.\"<ref>[https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/the-lancet-editor-s-selective-amnesia 'The Lancet editor's selective amnesia'], ''Spectator'', 27/3/20; [https://labourbriefing.org/blog/2020/3/26/the-editor-of-the-lancet-speaks 'The editor of the Lancet speaks out on coronavirus'], ''Labour Briefing'', 26/3/20; Dr. Richard Horton [https://twitter.com/richardhorton1/status/1223264064719216640 Tweet, 31/1/20].</ref>\n\nBy 7 March, Horton's was calling on the UK Government to \"act more decisively. They must abandon their fears of the negative short-term public and economic consequences that may follow from restricting public freedoms.\" And, on 10 March, he called for the \"urgent implementation of social distancing and closure policies.\"<ref>[https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30522-5/fulltext 'COVID-19: too little, too late'], Editorial, ''The Lancet'', 7/3/20; [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/squashing-sombrero-has-government-got-coronavirus-strategy-right/ 'Has the Government got its coronavirus strategy right'], ''Daily Telegraph'', 13/3/20.</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Horton strongly criticised the Government's initial plans \"to allow a controlled epidemic\", saying: \"Any numerate school student could make the calculation. With a mortality of 1% among 60% of a population of some 66 million people, the UK could expect almost 400,000 deaths.\"<ref>Richard Horton, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-uk-expert-advice-wrong 'Scientists have been sounding the alarm on coronavirus for months. Why did Britain fail to act''], ''Guardian'', 26/3/20.</ref>\n\nThen on 26 March, he said: \"We knew in the last week of January that this was coming. The message from China was absolutely clear that a new virus with pandemic potential was hitting cities. ... We knew that eleven weeks ago and then we wasted February when we could have acted.\" And, on 28 March, Horton's ''Lancet'' editorial stated that, having seen January's reports from China, the authorities \"had a duty to immediately put the NHS and British public on high alert.\"<ref> [https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/the-lancet-editor-s-selective-amnesia 'The Lancet editor's selective amnesia'], ''The Spectator'', 27/3/20; [https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30727-3/fulltext 'COVID-19 and the NHS \"a national scandal\"'], ''The Lancet'', Editorial, 28/3/20.</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the NHS Coronavirus director, [[Keith Willett]], responded to Horton saying that the NHS had \"declared a Level Four - the highest - National Emergency on January 30\". (This declaration, however, was not publicised until 3 March so it is unclear if Willett intended this as a response to Horton's ''Lancet'' editorial.)<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-nhs-uk-lancet-editor-richard-horton-a9431336.html 'Coronavirus: UK response means NHS staff and patients will \"die unnecessarily\", Lancet editor says'], ''The Independent'', 29/3/20; [https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/03/nhs-declares-coronavirus-level-four-incident-highest-category-12343608/ 'NHS declares coronavirus to be Level Four incident - the highest category'], ''Metro'', 3/3/20.</ref>\n\n===Awards and honours===\nIn 2007, Horton received the [[Edinburgh Medal]]<ref>\"Edinburgh Medal\". (Press release) 2015. Retrieved 6 January 2016. [http://www.sciencefestival.co.uk/edinburgh-medal Edinburgh International Science Festival website]</ref> for scientific and professional contributions to the understanding and well-being of humanity and in 2009 a recognition of contributions to public health from Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health.<ref>\"Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health Awards Dean\u2019s Medal to Richard Horton\" (Press release) Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health. 18 May 2009. Retrieved 6 January 2016. [http://www.jhsph.edu/news/news-releases/2009/horton-dean-medal.html Johns Hopkins website]</ref>\n\nHorton was elected a [[Fellow of the Academy of Medical Sciences]] (FMedSci)<ref name=fmedsci>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-richard-horton/|title=Professor Richard Horton - The Academy of Medical Sciences|website=acmedsci.ac.uk|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuffieldtrust.org.uk/about/our-people/senior-associates/dr-richard-horton|title=People|date=20 December 2016|website=Nuffieldtrust.org.uk|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> in 1998 and is a [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal College of Physicians]] (FRCP).<ref name=whoswho/> Horton is an honorary doctor at [[University of Troms\u00f8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalhealth.no/articles/global-health-icon-appointed-honorary-doctor-at-uit-the-arctic-university-of-norway|date=17 Oct 2018|website=Globalhealth.no|title=Global health icon appointed Honorary Doctor at UiT The Arctic University of Norway|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHorton married Ingrid Johanna Wolfe in 1998 and has one daughter.<ref name=whoswho/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Medicine|United Kingdom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horton, Richard}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bristol Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Physicians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Medical journal editors]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Richard Horton (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Richard Horton\n| native_name = Richard Charles Horton\n| native_name_lang = \n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRCP|FMedSci|size=100}}\n| image       =   Dr. Richard Horton, Editor in Chief, the Lancet (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = Richard Horton in 2013\n| birth_date  =   {{birth date and age|df=y|1961|12|29}}<ref name=whoswho/>\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  =   <!--{{death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|1961|12|29}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| residence   = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields      = \n| workplaces  = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[The Lancet]]''\n* [[Royal Free Hospital]]}}\n| patrons     = \n| education   = [[Bristol Grammar School]]<ref name=whoswho/>\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Birmingham]] (BSc, MB ChB)\n| thesis_title =  <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =   <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =   <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = \n| spouse      =   {{marriage|Ingrid Johanna Wolfe|1988}}<ref name=whoswho/>\n| partner     =   <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children    = 1 daughter<ref name=whoswho/>\n| signature   =   <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =   {{URL|https://www.theguardian.com/profile/richardhorton}}\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Richard Charles Horton''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRCP|FMedSci}} (born 29 December 1961) is [[editor-in-chief]] of ''[[The Lancet]]'', a [[United Kingdom]]\u2013based [[medical journal]].<ref name=whoswho>{{Who's Who | author=Anon|surname = Horton | othernames = Dr Richard Charles | id = U20825 | year = 2014 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U20825}} </ref><ref name=scopus>{{Scopus|id=26643541300}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1001/jama.276.8.637| pmid = 8773637| title = Improving the quality of reporting of randomized controlled trials. The CONSORT statement| journal = JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association| volume = 276| issue = 8| pages = 637\u2013639| year = 1996| last1 = Begg | first1 = C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(11)60393-0| title = Priority actions for the non-communicable disease crisis| journal = The Lancet| volume = 377| issue = 9775| pages = 1438\u201347| year = 2011| last1 = Beaglehole | first1 = R. | last2 = Bonita | first2 = R. | last3 = Horton | first3 = R. | last4 = Adams | first4 = C. | last5 = Alleyne | first5 = G. | last6 = Asaria | first6 = P. | last7 = Baugh | first7 = V. | last8 = Bekedam | first8 = H. | last9 = Billo | first9 = N. | last10 = Casswell | first10 = S. | last11 = Cecchini | first11 = M. | last12 = Colagiuri | first12 = R. | last13 = Colagiuri | first13 = S. | last14 = Collins | first14 = T. | last15 = Ebrahim | first15 = S. | last16 = Engelgau | first16 = M. | last17 = Galea | first17 = G. | last18 = Gaziano | first18 = T. | last19 = Geneau | first19 = R. | last20 = Haines | first20 = A. | last21 = Hospedales | first21 = J. | last22 = Jha | first22 = P. | last23 = Keeling | first23 = A. | last24 = Leeder | first24 = S. | last25 = Lincoln | first25 = P. | last26 = McKee | first26 = M. | last27 = MacKay | first27 = J. | last28 = Magnusson | first28 = R. | last29 = Moodie | first29 = R. | last30 = Mwatsama | first30 = M. | display-authors = 29 | pmid=21474174}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(96)90137-3| pmid = 8606606| title = Surgical research or comic opera: Questions, but few answers| journal = The Lancet| volume = 347| issue = 9007| pages = 984\u2013985| year = 1996| last1 = Horton | first1 = R. }}</ref><ref name=youtube>{{YouTube|id=v7BzM5mxN5U Richard Horton speech at Time to Go anti-war demonstration in Manchester on 2006-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1001/jama.286.10.1232| pmid = 11559271| title = Sponsorship, Authorship, and Accountability| journal = JAMA| volume = 286| issue = 10| pages = 1232\u20134| year = 2001| last1 = Davidoff | first1 = F. | pmc = 81460}}</ref><ref name=moribund>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61050-3| title = Offline: The moribund body of medical history| journal = The Lancet| volume = 384| issue = 9940| pages = 292| year = 2014| last1 = Horton | first1 = R. }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nHorton studied at [[Bristol Grammar School]]<ref name=whoswho/> from 1969 to 1980 and at the [[University of Birmingham]] from 1980 to 1986, receiving his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in physiology in 1983, and his [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery]] degree 1986. He completed his general medical training in Birmingham before moving to the [[Royal Free Hospital]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1990, Horton joined ''[[The Lancet]]'' as an assistant editor and moved to New York as North American editor in 1993. Two years later he returned to the UK to become Editor-in-Chief.\n\nHorton served as a medical columnist for ''[[The Observer]]'' and writes for ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'' and ''[[The New York Review of Books]]''. His book about controversies in modern medicine, ''Second Opinion: Doctors, Diseases and Decisions in Modern Medicine'', was published in 2003. (In the United States, it was published under the title ''Health Wars: On the Global Front Lines of Modern Medicine''.)\n\nIn 2005 he was a member of the working party and subsequently wrote the report for the [[Royal College of Physicians]]' inquiry into the future of medical professionalism \u2013 \"Doctors in Society\" (2005). He also chaired the [[Royal College of Physicians]]' Working Party on Physicians and the Pharmaceutical Industry; co-chaired a [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) Scientific Advisory Group on Clinical Trials Registration;<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1056/NEJMe048225| title = Clinical Trial Registration: A Statement from the International Committee of Medical Journal Editors| journal = New England Journal of Medicine| volume = 351| issue = 12| pages = 1250\u20131| year = 2004| last1 = De Angelis | first1 = C. | last2 = Drazen | first2 = J. M. | last3 = Frizelle | first3 = F. A. | last4 = Haug | first4 = C. | last5 = Hoey | first5 = J. | last6 = Horton | first6 = R. | last7 = Kotzin | first7 = S. | last8 = Laine | first8 = C. | last9 = Marusic | first9 = A. | last10 = Overbeke | first10 = A. J. P. M. | last11 = Schroeder | first11 = T. V. | last12 = Sox | first12 = H. C. | last13 = Weyden | first13 = M. B. V. D. | pmid=15356289}}</ref> chaired the Board of the Health Metrics Network; sat on the External Reference Group for WHO's Research Strategy; and is an External Advisory Board Member for the WHO European Region.<ref name=abouthtelancet/> Currently, he co-chairs the independent Expert Review Group on Information and Accountability for Women's and Children' Health. He is also a Council member of both the Academy of Medical Sciences and the University of Birmingham.\n\nHorton was the first President of the World Association of Medical Editors, and is a Past-President of the US [[Council of Science Editors]] (2005\u201306). He is an honorary professor at the [[London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]], the [[University College London]], and the [[University of Oslo]]. He is a Fellow of both of the Royal College of Physicians and of the UK's [[Academy of Medical Sciences]].<ref name=abouthtelancet>{{cite web | url=http://www.thelancet.com/lancet-about | title=About the Lancet | publisher=[[The Lancet]] | accessdate=2013-09-03}}</ref> In 2011, he was elected to the US [[Institute of Medicine]].<ref name=pmc558552>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.331.7507.53 |pmc=558552 |year=2005 |last1=Watts |first1=G |title=A right royal spat |journal=BMJ : British Medical Journal |volume=331 |issue=7507 |pages=53 }}</ref><ref>\"IOM Elects 65 New Members, Five Foreign Associates\" (Press release). Institute of Medicine. 17 October 2011. Retrieved 6 January 2016.[http://iom.nationalacademies.org/Global/News%20Announcements/2011-New-Members.aspx Institute of Medicine website]</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Horton was appointed to a research and analytical management panel as a Senior Associate of The [[Nuffield Trust]], a major independent health policy institution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuffieldtrust.org.uk/media-centre/press-releases/nuffield-trust-rejuvenates|title=Media centre|date=31 January 2017|website=Nuffieldtrust.org.uk|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> In 2016, he was appointed by [[United Nations Secretary-General]] [[Ban Ki-moon]] to an expert group advising the High-Level Commission on Health Employment and Economic Growth, which was co-chaired by presidents [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] of [[France]] and [[Jacob Zuma]] of [[South Africa]].<ref>[http://www.who.int/hrh/com-heeg/hrh_heeg_bios/en/ High-Level Commission on Health Employment and Economic Growth \u2013 Expert Group] [[World Health Organization]].</ref> In 2017, he served on the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) /[[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] (UNHCR) High-Level Working Group on the Health and Human Rights of Women, Children and Adolescents, chaired by [[Tarja Halonen]] and [[Hina Jilani]].<ref>[http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/255540/1/9789241512459-eng.pdf Leading the realization of human rights to health and through health: Report of the High-Level Working Group on the Health and Human Rights of Women, Children and Adolescents (2017)] [[World Health Organization]].</ref>\n\n=== Climate change and health professionals ===\nA few days after the word-wide mobilisation promoted by the activist movement [[Extinction Rebellion]], Horton asserts in a video that health professionals should involve themselves directly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/life/1317926/video-lancet-editor-richard-horton-urges-medical-licensing-body-not-punish-doctors|title=Video: Lancet editor Richard Horton urges medical licensing body not to punish doctors in Extinction Rebellion protests|date=2019-10-25|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref> He started by saying:<ref>{{Citation|title=Health and Climate - Richard Horton, The Lancet|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2x6sBfV64N4|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref>\n\n{{Block quote|The climate emergency that we're facing today is the most important existential crisis facing the human species. And since medicine is all about protecting and strengthening the human species, it should be absolutely foundational to the practice of what we do every single day.\n\nThe [[General Medical Council|GMC]] [General Medical Council] published an extremely important document, which guides all health professionals, \"Duties of a doctor\". The duties of a doctor are first and foremost to an individual patient or to the public that they serve.\n\nThe climate crisis is one of the most, I would say ''the most'', existential crisis facing our communities in the world today. Doctors and all health professionals have a responsibility, an obligation, to engage in all kinds of non-violent social protests to address the climate emergency. That is the duty of a doctor. [...]}}\n\n===Denial of retraction of discredited vaccine paper===\n{{see also|The Lancet#Controversies}}\n\nOn 28 February 1998 Horton published a controversial paper by Dr [[Andrew Wakefield]] and 12 co-authors with the title \u201cIleal-lymphoid-nodular hyperplasia, non-specific colitis, and pervasive developmental disorder in children\" suggesting that vaccines could cause autism. The publication of the paper set off a sharp decline in vaccinations in Europe and America and in subsequent years globally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/03/health/research/03lancet.html|title=British Journal Retracts Paper Linking Autism and Vaccines|first=Gardiner|last=Harris|date=2 February 2010|accessdate=8 June 2018|website=Nytimes.com}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the Health Protection Agency attributed a large measles outbreak in 2008 and 2009 to a concurrent drop in the number of children receiving the MMR vaccine. Pockets of measles \u2014 which can be fatal \u2014have also cropped up in Canada and the United States as a result of parents\u2019 refusal to vaccinate.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Lancet retracts 12-year-old article linking autism to MMR vaccines|first=Laura|last=Eggertson|date=9 March 2010|journal=CMAJ|volume=182|issue=4|pages=E199\u2013E200|doi=10.1503/cmaj.109-3179|pmid=20142376|pmc=2831678}}</ref>\n\nHorton was heavily criticised for refusing to take action for so long. He was finally forced to retract the paper in February 2010 after the General Medical Council, which oversees doctors in Britain, said that \"there was a biased selection of patients in ''The Lancet'' paper\" and that Wakefield's \"conduct in this regard was dishonest and irresponsible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/HEALTH/02/02/lancet.retraction.autism/index.html|title=Medical journal retracts study linking autism to vaccine|website=Cnn.com|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Horton defended his position by saying \"I do not regret publishing the original Wakefield paper. Progress in medicine depends on the free expression of new ideas. I worked at the Royal Free from 1988 to 1990 and met him on many occasions. He is a committed, engaging, and charismatic clinician and scientist. He asks big questions about diseases - what are their ultimate causes? - and his ambition often brings quick and impressive results.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://briandeer.com/mmr/horton-wakefield.htm|title=Andrew Wakefield \u2013 the fraud investigation \u2013 Brian Deer|website=briandeer.com|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> However, there are groups criticising Horton for contributing to the ongoing dramatic drop of vaccination of children in Europe and America that causes several epidemics and deaths by delaying the retraction of the paper for 12 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-39419976|title=Measles outbreak across Europe|date=28 March 2017|accessdate=8 June 2018|website=Bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n===Royal Society===\nIn the 11 May 2005 ''The Lancet'', Horton criticized the ancient British scientific group, the [[Royal Society]], under [[Martin Rees|Lord Rees]] for its neglect of medicine.<ref name=pmc558552/> Professor Mark Pepys and thirty other society members responded. A few years earlier the society and the journal had taken different positions in a scientific reporting debate known as the [[Pusztai affair]] involving research on genetically modified potatoes.\n\n===Professor Sir Roy Meadow===\nHorton published an article in 2005 supporting Professor Sir [[Roy Meadow]] who had been charged with serious professional misconduct by the GMC for giving erroneous and seriously misleading evidence in the [[Sally Clark]] trial. This was especially controversial as the article appeared whilst the GMC proceedings were still under away and was published on the first day of Meadow's defence. The article \"incensed\" Clark, a solicitor who had been the victim of a serious miscarriage of justice. With the support of erroneous statistical (and other) evidence from Meadow the prosecution wrongly convicted her of murder and she spent over three years in prison before her successful second appeal.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)66798-0 |pmid=15993209 |title=In defence of Roy Meadow |journal=The Lancet |volume=366 |issue=9479 |pages=3\u20135 |year=2005 |last1=Horton |first1=Richard }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/4641587.stm|title=Cot death expert defends evidence|date=1 July 2005|accessdate=8 June 2018|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHer husband wrote a rebuttal letter to ''The Lancet'' in order to correct Horton's 'many inaccuracies and one-sided opinions' and to prevent them prejudicing independent observers. Dr [[James Le Fanu]], medical practitioner and writer, also wrote to ''The Lancet'' in the same issue and described Horton's words as 'mischief'.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)67048-1 |pmid=16084242 |title=Roy Meadow |journal=The Lancet |volume=366 |issue=9484 |pages=449\u2013450 |year=2005 |last1=Clark |first1=Stephen }}</ref> The Clark family issued a statement addressing and countering with established fact each of the points making up Horton's biased support of Meadow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sallyclark.org.uk/Lancet050701.html|title=Sally Clark: Statement to the Lancet 1.7.05|website=Sallyclark.org.uk|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Iraq===\n{{Main|Lancet surveys of Iraq War casualties|Casualties of the Iraq War}}\nAt the ''Time to Go Demo'' of 23 September 2006, Horton accused American president [[George W. Bush]] and British prime minister [[Tony Blair]] of \"lies\" and \"killing children\" in [[Iraq]].  On 11 October, ''The Lancet'' published new estimates of the death toll of Iraqi citizens after the US-led [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion in 2003]], putting it at a total of 655,000. Some supporters of the invasion of Iraq dismissed it for what they claimed was flawed methodology.<ref>{{cite news|title= Huge gaps in Iraq death estimates|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/6045112.stm|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=12 October 2006 | first=Paul | last=Reynolds}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Critics attack huge Iraqi casualty figures|url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/irq061012|publisher=[[Radio Netherlands]]|date=12 October 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061207153847/http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/irq061012|archivedate=7 December 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Lancet' back at centre of controversy|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article1842560.ece|publisher=The Independent|date=13 October 2006|location=London|first=Ben|last=Russell|accessdate=2010-05-22|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001313/http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article1842560.ece|archivedate=1 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some opponents of the invasion questioned its reliability due to its extreme divergence from other data on the conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iraqbodycount.org/press/pr14.php|title=Iraq Body Count Press Release 14 (16 Oct 2006) :: Iraq Body Count|website=Iraqbodycount.org|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Some journals and statistical experts were supportive. Other experts in the field were not convinced, saying the estimates were \"high, and probably way too high\",<ref>{{cite news | url=http://blog.washingtonpost.com/worldopinionroundup/2006/10/is_iraqs_civilian_death_toll_h.html | work=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=2010-05-22 | title=Is Iraq's Civilian Death Toll 'Horrible' -- Or Worse? | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011180035/http://blog.washingtonpost.com/worldopinionroundup/2006/10/is_iraqs_civilian_death_toll_h.html | archivedate=11 October 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and that the authors had published a \"misinterpretation of their own figures\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2007/01/28/2003346700 |title=The civilian death toll in Iraq war proves a nebulous statistic |last= Daponte |first=Beth Osborne |date=January 28, 2007 |website=[[Taipei Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303193139/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2007/01/28/2003346700 |archive-date= March 3, 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref> \nOthers were incredulous that the survey could have been performed as reported under such dangerous conditions.<ref name=iraqdeathtoll>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/443728a| title = Iraqi death toll withstands scrutiny| journal = Nature| year = 2006| last1 = Giles | first1 = J.| pmid=17051169| volume=443| issue = 7113| pages=728\u20139| doi-access = free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.314.5798.396| pmid = 17053114| title = Epidemiology: Iraqi Death Estimates Called Too High; Methods Faulted| journal = Science| volume = 314| issue = 5798| pages = 396\u20137| year = 2006| last1 = Bohannon | first1 = John| authorlink1 = John Bohannon}}</ref>\n\nIraq's health minister estimated during a press conference in November 2006 that between 100,000 and 150,000 people had died since the invasion in 2003, based on an estimate of around 100 deaths per day brought to morgues and hospitals during 2006,<ref>{{cite news|title=Iraq issues controversial death toll|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/08e4ce42-70dc-11db-8e0b-0000779e2340.html|work=[[Financial Times]]|date=10 November 2006}}</ref> while saying that the ''Lancet'' estimates were an \"exaggerated number\".<ref name=\"IHT\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/11/09/europe/EU_GEN_Austria_Iraqis_Killed.php |title=Iraqi health minister estimates as many as 150,000 Iraqis killed by insurgents |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |date=November 9, 2006 |website=[[International Herald Tribune]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918000905/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/11/09/europe/EU_GEN_Austria_Iraqis_Killed.php |archive-date=2008-09-18 |url-status=dead |access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\n===Open Letter for the People of Gaza===\n\nIn August 2014 ''The Lancet'' published An Open letter for the people of Gaza,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61044-8| pmid = 25064592| title = An open letter for the people in Gaza| journal = The Lancet| volume = 384| issue = 9941| pages = 397\u2013398| year = 2014| last1 = Manduca | first1 = P. | last2 = Chalmers | first2 = I. | last3 = Summerfield | first3 = D. | last4 = Gilbert | first4 = M. | last5 = Ang | first5 = S. }}</ref> criticising Israel in the wake of the [[2014 Gaza conflict]].\n\nHorton responded to criticism of the letter by saying that it was \"a [[smear campaign]]\" and that he didn't \"honestly see what all this has to do with the Gaza letter. I have no plans to retract the letter, and I would not retract the letter even if it was found to be substantiated\".<ref name= Lazareva/> However, Horton subsequently came to Israel's [[Rambam Hospital]] for a visit and said that he \"deeply, deeply regret[ted] the completely unnecessary polarization that publication of the letter by Paola Manduca caused\".<ref name= Lazareva>{{cite news | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author= Lazareva, Inna|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/israel/11137943/Lancet-editor-apologises-for-Gaza-article-by-scientists-who-promoted-Ku-Klux-Klan.html | title=Lancet editor apologises for Gaza article by scientists who promoted Ku Klux Klan | date=3 October 2014 | accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.618899 | work=[[Haaretz]]|title=In Israel, Lancet editor regrets publishing open letter on Gaza | date=3 October 2014 | accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Health/The-Lancet-editor-relents-on-medical-journals-unbalanced-attacks-on-Israel-377937 |author=Siegel-Itzkovich, Judy|work=[[Jerusalem Post]]|title=The Lancet editor relents on medical journal's unbalanced attacks on Israel | date=2 October 2014 | accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nProfessor Sir [[Mark Pepys]] wrote: \"The failure of the Menduca et al authors to disclose their extraordinary conflicts of interest\u2026 are the most serious, unprofessional and unethical errors. The transparent effort to conceal this vicious and substantially mendacious partisan political diatribe as an innocent humanitarian appeal has no place in any serious publication, let alone a professional medical journal, and would disgrace even the lowest of the gutter press.\" In addition, Pepys accused Horton personally saying that \"Horton\u2019s behavior in this case is consistent with his longstanding and wholly inappropriate use of ''The Lancet'' as a vehicle for his own extreme political views. It has greatly detracted from the former high standing of the journal.\" In response, Horton said: \"How can you separate politics and health? The two go hand-in-hand.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/11112930/Lancet-hijacked-in-anti-Israel-campaign.html | title=Lancet 'hijacked in anti-Israel campaign' | author= Wallis Simons, Jake |date=22 September 2014 | accessdate=2 October 2014|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus Pandemic===\n\nDr. Horton's initial response to the outbreak of [[Coronavirus]] was cautious, telling his Twitter followers on 24 January 2020 that Covid-19 probably \"has moderate transmissibility and relatively low pathogenicity.\" But, as evidence came in from China, on 29 January, he said: \"It must now surely be time to declare a Public Health Emergency of International Concern.\" And, on 31 January, he tweeted about \"draconian measures that limit population mobility.\"<ref>[https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/the-lancet-editor-s-selective-amnesia 'The Lancet editor's selective amnesia'], ''Spectator'', 27/3/20; [https://labourbriefing.org/blog/2020/3/26/the-editor-of-the-lancet-speaks 'The editor of the Lancet speaks out on coronavirus'], ''Labour Briefing'', 26/3/20; Dr. Richard Horton [https://twitter.com/richardhorton1/status/1223264064719216640 Tweet, 31/1/20].</ref>\n\nBy 7 March, Horton's was calling on the UK Government to \"act more decisively. They must abandon their fears of the negative short-term public and economic consequences that may follow from restricting public freedoms.\" And, on 10 March, he called for the \"urgent implementation of social distancing and closure policies.\"<ref>[https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30522-5/fulltext 'COVID-19: too little, too late'], Editorial, ''The Lancet'', 7/3/20; [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/squashing-sombrero-has-government-got-coronavirus-strategy-right/ 'Has the Government got its coronavirus strategy right'], ''Daily Telegraph'', 13/3/20.</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Horton strongly criticised the Government's initial plans \"to allow a controlled epidemic\", saying: \"Any numerate school student could make the calculation. With a mortality of 1% among 60% of a population of some 66 million people, the UK could expect almost 400,000 deaths.\"<ref>Richard Horton, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-uk-expert-advice-wrong 'Scientists have been sounding the alarm on coronavirus for months. Why did Britain fail to act''], ''Guardian'', 26/3/20.</ref>\n\nThen on 26 March, he said: \"We knew in the last week of January that this was coming. The message from China was absolutely clear that a new virus with pandemic potential was hitting cities. ... We knew that eleven weeks ago and then we wasted February when we could have acted.\" And, on 28 March, Horton's ''Lancet'' editorial stated that, having seen January's reports from China, the authorities \"had a duty to immediately put the NHS and British public on high alert.\"<ref> [https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/the-lancet-editor-s-selective-amnesia 'The Lancet editor's selective amnesia'], ''The Spectator'', 27/3/20; [https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30727-3/fulltext 'COVID-19 and the NHS \"a national scandal\"'], ''The Lancet'', Editorial, 28/3/20.</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the NHS Coronavirus director, [[Keith Willett]], responded to Horton saying that the NHS had \"declared a Level Four - the highest - National Emergency on January 30\". (This declaration, however, was not publicised until 3 March so it is unclear if Willett intended this as a response to Horton's ''Lancet'' editorial.)<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-nhs-uk-lancet-editor-richard-horton-a9431336.html 'Coronavirus: UK response means NHS staff and patients will \"die unnecessarily\", Lancet editor says'], ''The Independent'', 29/3/20; [https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/03/nhs-declares-coronavirus-level-four-incident-highest-category-12343608/ 'NHS declares coronavirus to be Level Four incident - the highest category'], ''Metro'', 3/3/20.</ref>\n\n===Awards and honours===\nIn 2007, Horton received the [[Edinburgh Medal]]<ref>\"Edinburgh Medal\". (Press release) 2015. Retrieved 6 January 2016. [http://www.sciencefestival.co.uk/edinburgh-medal Edinburgh International Science Festival website]</ref> for scientific and professional contributions to the understanding and well-being of humanity and in 2009 a recognition of contributions to public health from Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health.<ref>\"Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health Awards Dean\u2019s Medal to Richard Horton\" (Press release) Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health. 18 May 2009. Retrieved 6 January 2016. [http://www.jhsph.edu/news/news-releases/2009/horton-dean-medal.html Johns Hopkins website]</ref>\n\nHorton was elected a [[Fellow of the Academy of Medical Sciences]] (FMedSci)<ref name=fmedsci>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-richard-horton/|title=Professor Richard Horton - The Academy of Medical Sciences|website=acmedsci.ac.uk|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuffieldtrust.org.uk/about/our-people/senior-associates/dr-richard-horton|title=People|date=20 December 2016|website=Nuffieldtrust.org.uk|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> in 1998 and is a [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal College of Physicians]] (FRCP).<ref name=whoswho/> Horton is an honorary doctor at [[University of Troms\u00f8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalhealth.no/articles/global-health-icon-appointed-honorary-doctor-at-uit-the-arctic-university-of-norway|date=17 Oct 2018|website=Globalhealth.no|title=Global health icon appointed Honorary Doctor at UiT The Arctic University of Norway|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHorton married Ingrid Johanna Wolfe in 1998 and has one daughter.<ref name=whoswho/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Medicine|United Kingdom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horton, Richard}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bristol Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Physicians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Medical journal editors]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n", "name_user": "NHS1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCoronavirus Pandemic", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Horton_(editor)"}
{"title_page": "Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres", "text_new": "{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Men's 200 metres\n|games = 1984 Summer\n|image =\n|caption =\n|venue = [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]\n|dates = {{Date|1984-8-6}} (heats and quarter-finals)<br />{{Date|1984-8-8}} (semi-finals and finals)\n|competitors = 76\n|nations = 58\n|win_value = 19.80 {{OlyR|athletics}}\n|longnames = yes\n|gold = [[Carl Lewis]]\n|goldNOC = USA\n|silver = [[Kirk Baptiste]]\n|silverNOC = USA\n|bronze = [[Thomas Jefferson (athlete)|Thomas Jefferson]]\n|bronzeNOC = USA\n|prev = [[Athletics at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|1980]]\n|next = [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|1988]]\n}}\n{{AthleticsAt1984SummerOlympics}}\nThe '''[[200 metres|Men's 200 metres]]''' at the '''[[Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Summer Olympics]]''' in [[Los Angeles, California]] had an entry list of 75 competitors, with ten qualifying heats (75), four quarterfinals (29), and two semi-finals (16) before the final (8) took off on Wednesday August 8, 1984.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1984/ATH/mens-200-metres.html |title=Athletics at the 1984 Los Angeles Games: Men's 200 metres |accessdate=16 July 2017 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\n==Medalists==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\" text-align:center; font-size:110%;\" width=\"35%\"\n|- \n|{{OlympicGoldMedalist|[[Carl Lewis]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{OlympicSilverMedalist|[[Kirk Baptiste]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{OlympicBronzeMedalist|[[Thomas Jefferson (athlete)|Thomas Jefferson]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|}\n\n==Abbreviations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\" text-align:center; font-size:110%;\" width=\"35%\"\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"ccffcc\"| '''Q''' || automatic qualification\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"ddffdd\"| '''q''' || qualification by rank\n|-\n|'''DNS''' || did not start\n|-\n|'''NM''' || no mark\n|-\n|'''OR''' || olympic record\n|-\n