n's 200 metres|1980 Men's Olympic 200 metres (Moscow)]]\n* [[1982 European Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|1982 Men's European Championships 200 metres (Athens)]]\n* [[1983 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|1983 Men's World Championships 200 metres (Helsinki)]]\n* [[Athletics at the Friendship Games \u2013 Men's 200 metres|1984 Friendship Games 200 metres (Moscow)]]\n* [[1986 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|1986 Men's European Championships 200 metres (Stuttgart)]]\n* [[1987 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|1987 Men's World Championships 200 metres (Rome)]]\n* [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|1988 Men's Olympic 200 metres (Seoul)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|en}} [http://sportslion.net/track/halloffame/LA1984/LA84-200mm.html Results]\n\n{{Olympics200metres}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics - Men's 200 metres}}\n[[Category:Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics|2]]\n[[Category:200 metres at the Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "Eschoryii", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athletics_at_the_1984_Summer_Olympics_%E2%80%93_Men%27s_200_metres"}
{"title_page": "Kait Parker", "text_new": "'''Kait Parker''' is an atmospheric scientist who recently worked for weather.com and [[The Weather Channel]] app.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://kaitparker.com/about/|title=About|date=2016-03-30|work=Kait Parker|access-date=2017-10-22|language=en-US}}</ref> She can also occasionally be seen on ''[[Good Morning America]]'' where she fills-in for meteorologist [[Rob Marciano]] on weekends.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/weatherkait/status/746675641181945856?lang=en|title=Good morning from @GMA ! I'm in all weekend :)pic.twitter.com/6eYlxdp6YB|last=Parker|first=Kait|date=2016-06-25|website=@weatherkait|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref> Prior to her role with weather.com, she was an on-camera meteorologist and host of [[America's Morning Headquarters]] Weekend Edition alongside [[Reynolds Wolf]]. She left [[The Weather Channel]] television network in early 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twctodayforums.com/forums/ocms/kait-parker-leaving-twc/|title=Kait Parker Leaving TWC|website=twctodayforums.com|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref> As of Labor Day weekend in 2019, she has been noticed contributing to weather.com, particularly in presenting and analyzing information about [[Hurricane Dorian]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2019-09-02-hurricane-dorian-florida-impacts-evacuations-cancellations|title=In Florida, Evacuations Underway, Flights Canceled For Hurricane Dorian|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> Furthermore, she frequently appears on Weather.com and The Weather Channel app in videos regarding climate change.\n\nParker made national headlines<ref>NPR. Don't Use Our Content to Mislead on Climate Change (2016) https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/12/07/504676327/weather-channel-tells-breitbart-not-to-use-its-content-to-mislead-on-climate-cha </ref> in 2016 with a rebuttal to [[Breitbart (website)|Breitbart]], a [[far-right]] website that used a video of her in an article claiming that the Earth was cooling rather than warming.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://weather.com/news/news/breitbart-misleads-americans-climate-change|title=Note to Breitbart: Earth Is Not Cooling, Climate Change Is Real and Please Stop Using Our Video to Mislead Americans {{!}} The Weather Channel|work=The Weather Channel|access-date=2017-10-22|language=en-US}}</ref> [[The Webby Awards]] chose the video as an honoree in the category of viral in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.webbyawards.com/winners/2017/film-video/general-film/viral/a-message-to-breitbart-from-weathercom/|title=A Message to Breitbart from Weather.com {{!}} The Webby Awards|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2016, Parker released a mini-[[documentary]] called ''Toxic Lake: The Untold Story of Lake Okeechobee'' about [[cyanobacteria]] ([[Blue-green Algae|blue-green algae]]) and water management in Florida where she was both producer and correspondent. The project has gone on to win [[Society of Professional Journalists|The Society of Professional Journalists]]' top honor for Digital Video and nominated for the [[News & Documentary Emmy Award|News and Documentary Emmy Awards]] for Outstanding Science and Environmental Reporting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spj.org/sdxa16.asp|title=Society of Professional Journalists Sigma Delta Chi Award Winners}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://weather.com/news/news/the-weather-channel-nominated-two-emmys|title=Weather.com Nominated for Two Emmys in Latest of Several Major Awards {{!}} The Weather Channel|work=The Weather Channel|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref>  \n\nShe was also named to the [[Grist (magazine)|Grist]] 50 list of Climate Fixers in 2017 and was featured in [[Marie Claire]] Magazine's first issue on sustainability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grist.org/grist-50/2017/|title=Grist 50: Meet the Fixers|website=Grist|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.marieclaire.com/career-advice/news/a28514/meet-meteorologist-kait-parker-climate-change/|title=Meet Meteorologist Kait Parker: The Woman Debunking Fake News Surrounding Climate Change|date=2017-07-27|work=Marie Claire|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en}}</ref>  \n\nParker has a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Atmospheric Science]] from [[University of Missouri|The University of Missouri]] in May 2009. Parker has also earned her [[Certified Broadcast meteorologist|Certified Broadcast Meteorologist]] Seal of Approval from the [[American Meteorological Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvcontract.com/clients/kait-parker|title=TV Contract   \u00bb Kait Parker|website=tvcontract.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref>\n\nParker began her career by filling-in at [[KOMU-TV]] in Columbia, MO in 2006 while still enrolled at the University of Missouri. Upon graduation in May 2009, she became weekday morning and midday meteorologist for [[WAKA-TV]] in Montgomery, AL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centralalabamatv.blogspot.com/2009/05/more-details-on-meteorologist-kait.html|title=Central Alabama TV: More Details on Meteorologist Kait Praker|last=Tv|first=Central Alabama|date=2009-05-27|website=Central Alabama TV|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref> From there she went on to [[WPTV-TV]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfltv.com/2010/kait-parker-joins-wptv/|title=Kait Parker Joins WPTV - SFLTV - South Florida TV|last=admin|date=2010-12-13|work=SFLTV - South Florida TV|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref> in West Palm Beach, FL where she was first hired as weekend meteorologist but was quickly put into a weekday role. Parker left WPTV-TV in early 2014 and went to work for [[The Weather Channel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/wptv-meteorologist-kait-parker-joins-the-weather-channel/111984|title=WPTV Meteorologist Kait Parker Joins The Weather Channel|website=www.adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref>\n\nParker was born and raised in [[Grapevine, Texas]] and she often points to her mother and father as the source of her interest in science. She is currently married and looks to be pregnant with her first child, although it is unconfirmed.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|7421720}} https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7421720/ retrieved September 5, 2019\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Kait}}\n[[Category:Women meteorologists]]\n[[Category:American television meteorologists]]\n[[Category:People from Grapevine, Texas]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Kait Parker''' is an atmospheric scientist who recently worked for weather.com and [[The Weather Channel]] app.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://kaitparker.com/about/|title=About|date=2016-03-30|work=Kait Parker|access-date=2017-10-22|language=en-US}}</ref> She can also occasionally be seen on ''[[Good Morning America]]'' where she fills-in for meteorologist [[Rob Marciano]] on weekends.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/weatherkait/status/746675641181945856?lang=en|title=Good morning from @GMA ! I'm in all weekend :)pic.twitter.com/6eYlxdp6YB|last=Parker|first=Kait|date=2016-06-25|website=@weatherkait|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref> Prior to her role with weather.com, she was an on-camera meteorologist and host of [[America's Morning Headquarters]] Weekend Edition alongside [[Reynolds Wolf]]. She left [[The Weather Channel]] television network in early 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twctodayforums.com/forums/ocms/kait-parker-leaving-twc/|title=Kait Parker Leaving TWC|website=twctodayforums.com|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref> As of Labor Day weekend in 2019, she has been noticed contributing to weather.com, particularly in presenting and analyzing information about [[Hurricane Dorian]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2019-09-02-hurricane-dorian-florida-impacts-evacuations-cancellations|title=In Florida, Evacuations Underway, Flights Canceled For Hurricane Dorian|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\nParker made national headlines<ref>NPR. Don't Use Our Content to Mislead on Climate Change (2016) https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/12/07/504676327/weather-channel-tells-breitbart-not-to-use-its-content-to-mislead-on-climate-cha </ref> in 2016 with a rebuttal to [[Breitbart (website)|Breitbart]], a [[far-right]] website that used a video of her in an article claiming that the Earth was cooling rather than warming.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://weather.com/news/news/breitbart-misleads-americans-climate-change|title=Note to Breitbart: Earth Is Not Cooling, Climate Change Is Real and Please Stop Using Our Video to Mislead Americans {{!}} The Weather Channel|work=The Weather Channel|access-date=2017-10-22|language=en-US}}</ref> [[The Webby Awards]] chose the video as an honoree in the category of viral in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.webbyawards.com/winners/2017/film-video/general-film/viral/a-message-to-breitbart-from-weathercom/|title=A Message to Breitbart from Weather.com {{!}} The Webby Awards|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2016, Parker released a mini-[[documentary]] called ''Toxic Lake: The Untold Story of Lake Okeechobee'' about [[cyanobacteria]] ([[Blue-green Algae|blue-green algae]]) and water management in Florida where she was both producer and correspondent. The project has gone on to win [[Society of Professional Journalists|The Society of Professional Journalists]]' top honor for Digital Video and nominated for the [[News & Documentary Emmy Award|News and Documentary Emmy Awards]] for Outstanding Science and Environmental Reporting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spj.org/sdxa16.asp|title=Society of Professional Journalists Sigma Delta Chi Award Winners}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://weather.com/news/news/the-weather-channel-nominated-two-emmys|title=Weather.com Nominated for Two Emmys in Latest of Several Major Awards {{!}} The Weather Channel|work=The Weather Channel|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref>  \n\nShe was also named to the [[Grist (magazine)|Grist]] 50 list of Climate Fixers in 2017 and was featured in [[Marie Claire]] Magazine's first issue on sustainability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grist.org/grist-50/2017/|title=Grist 50: Meet the Fixers|website=Grist|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.marieclaire.com/career-advice/news/a28514/meet-meteorologist-kait-parker-climate-change/|title=Meet Meteorologist Kait Parker: The Woman Debunking Fake News Surrounding Climate Change|date=2017-07-27|work=Marie Claire|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en}}</ref>  \n\nParker has a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Atmospheric Science]] from [[University of Missouri|The University of Missouri]] in May 2009. Parker has also earned her [[Certified Broadcast meteorologist|Certified Broadcast Meteorologist]] Seal of Approval from the [[American Meteorological Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvcontract.com/clients/kait-parker|title=TV Contract   \u00bb Kait Parker|website=tvcontract.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref>\n\nParker began her career by filling-in at [[KOMU-TV]] in Columbia, MO in 2006 while still enrolled at the University of Missouri. Upon graduation in May 2009, she became weekday morning and midday meteorologist for [[WAKA-TV]] in Montgomery, AL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centralalabamatv.blogspot.com/2009/05/more-details-on-meteorologist-kait.html|title=Central Alabama TV: More Details on Meteorologist Kait Praker|last=Tv|first=Central Alabama|date=2009-05-27|website=Central Alabama TV|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref> From there she went on to [[WPTV-TV]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfltv.com/2010/kait-parker-joins-wptv/|title=Kait Parker Joins WPTV - SFLTV - South Florida TV|last=admin|date=2010-12-13|work=SFLTV - South Florida TV|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref> in West Palm Beach, FL where she was first hired as weekend meteorologist but was quickly put into a weekday role. Parker left WPTV-TV in early 2014 and went to work for [[The Weather Channel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/wptv-meteorologist-kait-parker-joins-the-weather-channel/111984|title=WPTV Meteorologist Kait Parker Joins The Weather Channel|website=www.adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-16}}</ref>\n\nParker was born and raised in [[Grapevine, Texas]] and she often points to her mother and father as the source of her interest in science. She is currently married.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|7421720}} https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7421720/ retrieved September 5, 2019\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Kait}}\n[[Category:Women meteorologists]]\n[[Category:American television meteorologists]]\n[[Category:People from Grapevine, Texas]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "204.111.240.54", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added Content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kait_Parker"}
{"title_page": "SI 960", "text_new": "{{Short description|DEC and Israeli Standard 7-bit character encoding for Hebrew}}\n{{Redir|DEC Hebrew (7-bit)|the 8-bit character set|DEC Hebrew (8-bit)}}\n{{infobox character encoding\n|name = SI 960\n|alias = DEC Hebrew (7-bit)\n|standard = SI 960\n|kermit = hebrew-7\n|next = '''DEC:''' [[DEC Hebrew|DEC Hebrew (8-bit)]], <br/>'''SII:''' [[SI 1311]]\n|classification = 7-bit encoding, [[ISO/IEC 646#Derivatives for other alphabets|non-Latin adaptation of ISO 646]] with naturally ordered letters\n|basedon = [[ASCII]]\n|by = [[Digital Equipment Corporation|DEC]]\n}}\n\nThe [[Israeli Standards Institute]]'s Standard '''SI 960''' defines a 7-bit [[Hebrew]] [[code page]]. It is derived from, but does not conform to, [[ISO/IEC 646]]; more specifically, it follows [[ASCII]] except for the lowercase letters and backtick (<code>`</code>), which are replaced by the naturally ordered [[Hebrew alphabet]]. It is also known as '''DEC Hebrew (7-bit)''', because [[Digital Equipment Corporation|DEC]] standardized this character set before it became an international standard.<ref name=\"Kennelly_1991_DEC\"/> [[Kermit (protocol)|Kermit]] named it '''hebrew-7''' and '''HEBREW-7'''.<ref name=\"Kermit_Charsets\"/><ref name=\"Kermit_Hebrew\"/>\n\nThe [[Hebrew alphabet]] is mapped to positions 0x60\u20130x7A, on top of the lowercase Latin letters (and grave accent for aleph). 7-bit Hebrew is stored in visual order.\n\nThis mapping with the high bit set, i.e. with the Hebrew letters in 0xE0\u20130xFA, is also reflected in [[ISO 8859-8]].\n\n==Code page layout==\n\n{|{{chset-tableformat}}\n{{chset-table-header|SI 960<ref name=\"Kermit_Hebrew-7\"/>}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|0_<br/>0}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0000|[[Null character|NUL]]|0}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0001|[[Start of heading|SOH]]|1}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0002|[[Start of text|STX]]|2}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0003|[[End of text|ETX]]|3}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0004|[[End of transmission character|EOT]]|4}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0005|[[Enquiry character|ENQ]]|5}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0006|[[Acknowledge character|ACK]]|6}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0007|[[Bell character|BEL]]|7}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0008|[[Backspace|BS]]|8}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0009|[[Tab key|HT]]|9}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|000A|[[Line feed|LF]]|10}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|000B|[[Vertical tab|VT]]|11}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|000C|[[Form feed|FF]]|12}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|000D|[[Carriage return|CR]]|13}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|000E|[[Shift out|SO]]|14}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|000F|[[Shift in|SI]]|15}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|1_<br/>16}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0010|[[Data link escape|DLE]]|16}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0011|[[Device Control 1|DC1]]|17}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0012|[[Device Control 2|DC2]]|18}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0013|[[Device Control 3|DC3]]|19}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0014|[[Device Control 4|DC4]]|20}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0015|[[Negative acknowledge character|NAK]]|21}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0016|[[Synchronous idle|SYN]]|22}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0017|[[End of transmission block|ETB]]|23}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0018|[[Cancel character|CAN]]|24}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0019|[[End of medium|EM]]|25}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|001A|[[Substitute character|SUB]]|26}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|001B|[[Escape character|ESC]]|27}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|001C|[[File separator|FS]]|28}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|001D|[[Group separator|GS]]|29}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|001E|[[Record separator|RS]]|30}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|001F|[[Unit separator|US]]|31}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|2_<br/>32}}\n|{{chset-color-misc}}|{{chset-ctrl|0020|[[space character|SP]]|32}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0021|[[Exclamation mark|!]]|33}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0022|[[Quotation mark|&#x22;]]|34}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0023|[[Number sign|#]]|35}}\n|{{chset-color-graph}}|{{chset-cell|0024|[[Dollar sign|$]]|36}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0025|[[Percent sign|%]]|37}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0026|[[Ampersand|&amp;]]|38}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0027|[[Apostrophe|&#x27;]]|39}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0028|[[Parenthesis|(]]|40}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|0029|[[Parenthesis|)]]|41}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002A|[[Asterisk|*]]|42}}\n|{{chset-color-graph}}|{{chset-cell|002B|[[Plus and minus signs|+]]|43}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002C|[[Comma (punctuation)|,]]|44}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002D|[[Plus and minus signs|-]]|45}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002E|[[Full stop|.]]|46}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|002F|[[Slash (punctuation)|/]]|47}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|3_<br/>48}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0030|[[0 (number)|0]]|48}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0031|[[1 (number)|1]]|49}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0032|[[2 (number)|2]]|50}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0033|[[3 (number)|3]]|51}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0034|[[4 (number)|4]]|52}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0035|[[5 (number)|5]]|53}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0036|[[6 (number)|6]]|54}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0037|[[7 (number)|7]]|55}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0038|[[8 (number)|8]]|56}}\n|{{chset-color-digit}}|{{chset-cell|0039|[[9 (number)|9]]|57}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|003A|[[colon (punctuation)|&#x3A;]]|58}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|003B|[[semicolon|&#x3B;]]|59}}\n|{{chset-color-graph}}|{{chset-cell|003C|[[less-than sign|&#x3C;]]|60}}\n|{{ch