hset-cell|007C|[[Vertical bar|&#x7C;]]|124}}\n|{{chset-color-punct}}|{{chset-cell|007D|[[Braces (punctuation)|&#x7d;]]|125}}\n|{{chset-color-graph}}|{{chset-cell|007E|[[Tilde|~]]|126}}\n|{{chset-color-undef}}|\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[ISO/IEC 646]]\n*[[DEC National Replacement Character Set]] (NRCS)\n*[[SI 1311]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Kennelly_1991_DEC\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=GkajBQAAQBAJ |title=Digital Guide To Developing International Software |publisher=[[Digital Equipment Corporation]] |id=EY-F577E-DP |date=1991 |author-first=Cynthia |author-last=Hartman Kennelly |editor-first=Jacqueline |editor-last=Unch |edition=1 |isbn=1-55558-063-7<!-- |isbn=1-48329741-1 |ISBN=978-1-48329741-5 -->}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kermit_Charsets\">{{cite web |title=Character sets |publisher=[[Columbia University]] |work=[[Kermit (protocol)|Kermit]] |date=2000-01-01 |url=http://www.kermitproject.org/charsets.html |access-date=2017-02-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218085953/http://www.kermitproject.org/charsets.html |archive-date=2017-02-18}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kermit_Hebrew\">{{cite web |title=Hebrew Character Sets in Kermit 95 |work=Kermit 95 Manual |publisher=[[Columbia University]] |url=http://www.columbia.edu/kermit/k95manual/hebrew.html |access-date=2017-02-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218090226/http://www.columbia.edu/kermit/k95manual/hebrew.html |archive-date=2017-02-18}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kermit_Hebrew-7\">{{cite web |title=Hebrew 7-Bit Character Set |work=[[Kermit (protocol)|Kermit]] |publisher=[[Columbia University]] |url=ftp://kermit.columbia.edu/kermit/charsets/hebrew-7.txt |access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Hebrew encodings}}\n{{Character encoding}}\n\n[[Category:Character sets]]\n[[Category:SII standards]]\n", "name_user": "Drmccreedy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adjust color parameters based on Unicode properties and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Chset-cell documentation.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_960"}
{"title_page": "Halloween massacre (Angola)", "text_new": "The '''Halloween massacre''' (also known as the '''Three Day War''') refers to events which took place from October 30 to November 1, 1992 in [[Luanda]], [[Angola]] as part of the [[Angolan Civil War]].<ref name=Dictionary>[https://books.google.com/books?id=V_qm7zPo87oC&pg=PA33&lpg=PA33&dq=Angola+Halloween+Massacre&source=bl&ots=z4kRxXc_VX&sig=tcCDQm2tGVKOk4AFFfvAOtUCGnE&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result#PPA67,M1 Historical Dictionary of Angola by W. Martin James, Susan Herlin Broadhead] on Google Books</ref>\n\n==Context==\n\n=== The Angolan Civil War ===\nMain article: [[Angolan Civil War]]\n\nEver since its [[Angolan War of Independence|independence from Portugual]] in 1975, Angola was gripped in a civil war between the Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola ([[MPLA]]) and the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola ([[UNITA]])<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Fortna|first=Virginia Page|date=Winter\u2013Spring 2003|title=A Lost Chance for Peace: The Bicesse Accords in Angola|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43134444|journal=Georgetown Journal of International Affairs|volume=4|pages=74|via=JSTOR}}</ref>. The war was intensified by the direct and indirect involvement of outside superpowers who saw the conflict through the eyes of the [[Cold War]]. The MPLA, which claimed allegiance to [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist-Leninist]] ideology, [[Cuban intervention in Angola|recieved direct support]] from [[Cuba]] with the backing of the [[Soviet Union]] and other communist states<ref name=\":0\" />. Meanwhile, the UNITA sold itself as an anti-communist organization, recieving direct military support from [[South Africa]] with help from the [[United States]]<ref name=\":0\" />. Ferocious combat was waged during this time period but neither side was able to claim total victory over the other<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Pereira|first=Anthony W.|date=1994|title=The Neglected Tragedy: the Return to War in Angola, 1992\u20133|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1017/s0022278x00012520|journal=The Journal of Modern African Studies|volume=32|issue=1|pages=1\u201328|doi=10.1017/s0022278x00012520|issn=0022-278X|via=}}</ref>. By 1988, as the Cold War began to draw to a close, Cuba and South Africa withdrew their troops from the conflict<ref name=\":0\" />. Their withdrawal, coupled with the inability for either side to achieve total victory over the other, forced the MPLA the MPLA and UNITA to the negotiating table to negotiate a political settlement to the conflict<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\nThe Halloween massacre took place following the [[Angolan presidential election, 1992|1992 presidential and legislative elections]], which were the first in the country's history. The government party, the People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola ([[MPLA]]), claimed victory in these elections. The opposition movement turned political party, National Union for the Total Independence of Angola ([[UNITA]]), questioned the fairness of the election.  Because neither the MPLA nor UNITA obtained the required absolute majority of the presidential election, a follow-up election was necessary according to the constitution.\n\n==Events==\nAs both sides heightened war rhetoric, the MPLA attacked UNITA positions in Luanda. Fighting ensued, leading to the deaths of many prominent UNITA officials, including [[Jeremias Chitunda]], [[Elias Salupeto Pena]] and [[Aliceres Mango]], who were pulled from their vehicles and shot dead.<ref name=Dictionary/> Thousands of UNITA and [[National Liberation Front of Angola]] (FNLA) voters were massacred nationwide by MPLA forces over three days.<ref name=Multiple1992>National Society for Human Rights, ''Ending the Angolan Conflict'', Windhoek, Namibia, July 3, 2000; NSHR, Press Releases, September 12, 2000, May 16, 2001.</ref>\n\n==Results==\nOver 10,000 UNITA and FNLA followers were killed by MPLA forces,<ref name=Multiple1992>National Society for Human Rights, ''Ending the Angolan Conflict'', Windhoek, Namibia, July 3, 2000; NSHR, Press Releases, September 12, 2000, May 16, 2001.</ref> mostly of the [[Ovimbundu]] and [[Bakongo]] ethnic groups.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cidcm.umd.edu/mar/chronology.asp?groupId=54001 |title=Chronology for Bakongo in Angola |access-date=2008-12-24 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120804145116/http://www.cidcm.umd.edu/mar/chronology.asp?groupId=54001 |archive-date=2012-08-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other estimates, based on church figures, estimate 25,000 to 40,000 UNITA and FNLA supporters were killed.<ref name=Dictionary/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1990s in Angola]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Angola}}\n\n[[Category:1992 in Angola]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1992]]\n[[Category:Massacres of the Angolan Civil War]]\n[[Category:20th century in Luanda]]\n[[Category:Events in Luanda]]\n\n{{Angola-stub}}\n{{Africa-hist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Halloween massacre''' (also known as the '''Three Day War''') refers to events which took place from October 30 to November 1, 1992 in [[Luanda]], [[Angola]] as part of the [[Angolan Civil War]].<ref name=Dictionary>[https://books.google.com/books?id=V_qm7zPo87oC&pg=PA33&lpg=PA33&dq=Angola+Halloween+Massacre&source=bl&ots=z4kRxXc_VX&sig=tcCDQm2tGVKOk4AFFfvAOtUCGnE&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result#PPA67,M1 Historical Dictionary of Angola by W. Martin James, Susan Herlin Broadhead] on Google Books</ref>\n\n==Context==\n\n=== The Angolan Civil War ===\nMain article: [[Angolan Civil War]]\n\nEver since its [[Angolan War of Independence|independence from Portugual]] in 1975, Angola was gripped in a civil war between the Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola ([[MPLA]]) and the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola ([[UNITA]])<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Fortna|first=Virginia Page|date=Winter/Spring 2003|title=A Lost Chance for Peace: The Bicesse Accords in Angola|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43134444|journal=Georgetown Journal of International Affairs|volume=4|pages=74|via=JSTOR}}</ref>. The war was intensified by the direct and indirect involvement of outside superpowers who saw the conflict through the eyes of the [[Cold War]]. The MPLA, which claimed allegiance to [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist-Leninist]] ideology, [[Cuban intervention in Angola|recieved direct support]] from [[Cuba]] with the backing of the [[Soviet Union]] and other communist states<ref name=\":0\" />. Meanwhile, the UNITA sold itself as an anti-communist organization, recieving direct military support from [[South Africa]] with help from the [[United States]]<ref name=\":0\" />. Ferocious combat was waged during this time period but neither side was able to claim total victory over the other<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Pereira|first=Anthony W.|date=1994|title=The Neglected Tragedy: the Return to War in Angola, 1992\u20133|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1017/s0022278x00012520|journal=The Journal of Modern African Studies|volume=32|issue=1|pages=1\u201328|doi=10.1017/s0022278x00012520|issn=0022-278X|via=}}</ref>. By 1988, as the Cold War began to draw to a close, Cuba and South Africa withdrew their troops from the conflict<ref name=\":0\" />. Their withdrawal, coupled with the inability for either side to achieve total victory over the other, forced the MPLA the MPLA and UNITA to the negotiating table to negotiate a political settlement to the conflict<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\nThe Halloween massacre took place following the [[Angolan presidential election, 1992|1992 presidential and legislative elections]], which were the first in the country's history. The government party, the People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola ([[MPLA]]), claimed victory in these elections. The opposition movement turned political party, National Union for the Total Independence of Angola ([[UNITA]]), questioned the fairness of the election.  Because neither the MPLA nor UNITA obtained the required absolute majority of the presidential election, a follow-up election was necessary according to the constitution.\n\n==Events==\nAs both sides heightened war rhetoric, the MPLA attacked UNITA positions in Luanda. Fighting ensued, leading to the deaths of many prominent UNITA officials, including [[Jeremias Chitunda]], [[Elias Salupeto Pena]] and [[Aliceres Mango]], who were pulled from their vehicles and shot dead.<ref name=Dictionary/> Thousands of UNITA and [[National Liberation Front of Angola]] (FNLA) voters were massacred nationwide by MPLA forces over three days.<ref name=Multiple1992>National Society for Human Rights, ''Ending the Angolan Conflict'', Windhoek, Namibia, July 3, 2000; NSHR, Press Releases, September 12, 2000, May 16, 2001.</ref>\n\n==Results==\nOver 10,000 UNITA and FNLA followers were killed by MPLA forces,<ref name=Multiple1992>National Society for Human Rights, ''Ending the Angolan Conflict'', Windhoek, Namibia, July 3, 2000; NSHR, Press Releases, September 12, 2000, May 16, 2001.</ref> mostly of the [[Ovimbundu]] and [[Bakongo]] ethnic groups.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cidcm.umd.edu/mar/chronology.asp?groupId=54001 |title=Chronology for Bakongo in Angola |access-date=2008-12-24 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120804145116/http://www.cidcm.umd.edu/mar/chronology.asp?groupId=54001 |archive-date=2012-08-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other estimates, based on church figures, estimate 25,000 to 40,000 UNITA and FNLA supporters were killed.<ref name=Dictionary/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1990s in Angola]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Angola}}\n\n[[Category:1992 in Angola]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1992]]\n[[Category:Massacres of the Angolan Civil War]]\n[[Category:20th century in Luanda]]\n[[Category:Events in Luanda]]\n\n{{Angola-stub}}\n{{Africa-hist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix cite date error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halloween_massacre_(Angola)"}
{"title_page": "Kate Grenville", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image = Kate Grenville. Danielle Bagnato. Text Publishing.jpg\n| name        = Kate Grenville\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AO}}\n| caption     = Grenville in Melbourne, 2017\n| pseudonym   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth-date and age|14 October 1950}}\n| birth_place = [[Sydney, Australia]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Novelist, teacher of creative writing\n| nationality = Australian \n| period      = \n| genre       = General fiction, historical fiction, short stories\n| subject     = \n| movement    = \n| debut_works = \n| signature   = \n| website = {{url|http://kategrenville.com.au}}\n}}\n\n'''Catherine Elizabeth Grenville''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AO}} (born 14 October 1950) is an Australian author. She has published fifteen books, including fiction, non-fiction, biography, and books about the writing process. In 2001, she won the [[Orange Prize for Fiction|Orange Prize]] for ''[[The Idea of Perfection]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Neill|first1=Rosemary|title=A prize of one's own|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/a-prize-of-ones-own/news-story/4e87f8a36c0ab40502852e8c557444e9|accessdate=13 October 2017|work=The Australian}}</ref> and in 2006 she won the [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]] for ''[[The Secret River]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Australian writer wins book prize|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4803084.stm|date=14 March 2006|accessdate=13 October 2017|publisher=BBC}}</ref> ''The Secret River'' was also shortlisted for the [[Man Booker Prize]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kate Grenville, Australian novelist|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Kate-Grenville#ref945357|website=Encyclopaedia Britannica|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nHer novels have been published worldwide and have been translated into many languages. Three have been adapted into feature films.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kate Grenville|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0340300/|website=IMDb|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> ''The Secret River'' was adapted for the stage by [[Andrew Bovell]] and toured by the [[Sydney Theatre Company]] in 2019.<ref>Sydney Theatre Company (2019), ''The Secret River'', [[Edinburgh International Festival]] theatre programme.</ref>\n\n==Life==\n\nKate Grenville was born in Sydney in 1950, one of three children born to [[Ken Gee (judge)|Kenneth Grenville Gee]], a [[District Court of New South Wales|District Court]] judge and barrister; and Isobel Russell, a pharmacist.<ref name = \"Henderson\">Henderson (2008).</ref> She was educated at [[Cremorne Girls High School]], the [[University of Sydney]] (BA Hons) and the [[University of Colorado]] (MA). After completing her undergraduate degree at the University of Sydney, Grenville worked in the film industry, mostly editing documentaries at [[Film Australia]]. She has also been a teacher of [[creative writing]]. Between 1976 and 1980 she lived in London and Paris, and wrote fiction while supporting herself by doing film-editing, writing, and secretarial jobs. In 1980 she went to the [[University of Colorado at Boulder|University of Colorado]] at [[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder]] to do a master's degree in creative writing. She returned to Australia in 1983<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.users.bigpond.com/kgrenville/bio.html |title=Kate Grenville - My Life - a biographical note |accessdate=14 May 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501165305/http://www.users.bigpond.com/kgrenville/bio.html |archivedate= 1 May 2008 }}</ref> and became a sub-editor at [[SBS Television]] in the [[subtitle (captioning)|subtitling]] department. She won a literary grant in 1986 and left SBS to pursue her writing.<ref>Waldren, M. (2001), [http://members.optusnet.com.au/~waldrenm/kate.html \"Kismet Kate: An Interview with the Winner of the Orange Prize for Fiction 2001\"]. Retrieved 19 May 2007.</ref> Since the early 1990s she has been an Honorary Associate at the [[University of Sydney]].<ref>[http://www.usyd.edu.au/news/84.html?newsstoryid=1342 \"And now the Booker: Grenville's accolades keep coming\"], University of Sydney, 26 September 2006. Retrieved 2 August 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2006 she was awarded a Doctorate of Creative Arts by the [[University of Technology, Sydney]]<ref name=\"PE\">Peter Ellis, Interview with Kate Grenville, 1 August 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.newsroom.uts.edu.au/news/detail.cfm?ItemId=7032 \"Searching for the secret river\"], 6 December 2006. Retrieved 2 August 2009.</ref> under the supervision of [[Glenda Adams]] and Paula Hamilton. She has also been awarded an Honorary Doctorate of Letters from the University of Sydney,<ref>{{cite news|title=Outstanding individuals recognised in honorary degrees|url=http://sydney.edu.au/news/84.html?newsstoryid=10490|date=9 November 2012|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=University of Sydney}}</ref> the [[University of New South Wales|University of NSW]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Kate Grenville's letters|url=https://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/newsroom/articles/kate-grenvilles-letters/|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=University of New South Wales}}</ref> and [[Macquarie University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Celebrated Australian writer Kate Grenville receives an Honorary Degree|url=http://www.mq.edu.au/newsroom/2013/04/19/celebrated-australian-writer-kate-grenville-receives-an-honorary-doctorate/|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=Macquarie University}}</ref>\nIn 2017 she was awarded a Lifetime Achievement award from the Australia Council and in 2018 received an AO.\n\nGrenville has been married to Robert Steiner and cartoonist [[Bruce Petty]]. She lives in Sydney with her son and daughter. Her leisure activities include learning to play the cello<ref name=\"bio\"/> and performing in an amateur orchestra.\n\n==Career==\n\nKate Grenville's reputation as a short story writer was made by the publication in 1984 of her collection ''[[Bearded Ladies]]''.<ref name = \"Whitlock2\">Whitlock (1989), p. 2.</ref> On its publication, [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] wrote \"Here is someone who can really write\".{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n''[[Lilian's Story]]'' was her first published novel (1985) and won [[The Australian/Vogel Literary Award]]. It was loosely based on the story of [[Bea Miles]], known in Sydney for her eccentric public behaviour.<ref>{{cite web | first=Kate | last=Grenville | title =The Novelist as Barbarian | publisher =[[National Library of Australia]] | url =http://www.nla.gov.au/events/history/papers/Kate_Grenville%20.html | accessdate = 2015-07-12}}</ref> It has become one of Australia's best-loved novels and in 1996 was made into a film starring [[Ruth Cracknell]] and [[Toni Collette]]; Collette won the [[Australian Film Institute]] [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|award for supporting actress]] for her performance as the young Lilian.\n\n''[[Dreamhouse (novel)|Dreamhouse]]'' followed in 1986, and appeared as the 1994 film ''[[Traps (1994 film)|Traps]]''. ''[[Joan Makes History]]'' \u2013 the recipient of an Australian Bicentennial Commission \u2013 was published in 1988.\n\nIn 1994 Grenville returned to the characters and setting of ''Lilian's Story'' with a companion novel \u2013 ''[[Dark Places (Grenville novel)|Dark Places]]'' \u2013 that re-tells the events of the earlier novel from the point of view of Lilian's incestuous father. ''Dark Places'' won the [[Victorian Premier's Literary Award]] in 1995. (In the US this novel is titled ''Albion's Story''.)\n\n''[[The Idea of Perfection]]'' appeared in 2000 and won the Orange Prize for Fiction, at the time Britain's richest literary award.\n\nIn 2006 ''[[The Secret River]]'' was published, the first of Grenville's books that take Australia's colonial past, and relations with Australia's indigenous people, as their subject. ''The Secret River'' was inspired by the story of Grenville's own great-great-great grandfather, a [[Convicts in Australia|convict]] sent to Australia from London in 1806.  This book won the Commonwealth Prize,<ref>Richard Lea, [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/may/08/news.awardsandprizes \"Kate Grenville to meet the Queen\"], ''The Guardian'', 8 May 2006.</ref> the [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards#Christina Stead Prize for Fiction|Christina Stead Award]], and the [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards#Community Relations Commission Award|NSW Premier's Community Relations Prize]], and was shortlisted for the [[Man Booker Prize]].\n\n''Searching for The Secret River'' (2006) is a memoir about the research and writing of the novel, tracing the journey of the author's increasing awareness of how Australia's colonial past informs its present.\n\n''[[The Lieutenant (novel)|The Lieutenant]]'' (2008) is set thirty years earlier than ''The Secret River''. Based on the historical notebooks of Lieutenant [[William Dawes (British Marines officer)|William Dawes]], it tells the story of the friendship between a soldier with the [[First Fleet]] and a young [[Gadigal]] girl.  These two novels together explore something of the complexity of black-white relations in Australia's past.\n\n''[[Sarah Thornhill]]'' (2011) is the sequel to ''The Secret River'' and takes up the story of William Thornhill's youngest daughter. It can be read as a stand-alone novel, without reference to ''The Secret River''.\n\nHer latest book is ''One Life: My Mother's Story'', in which Grenville uses the fragments of memoir that her mother left to construct the story of a woman whose life - in some ways typical of her times, in other ways remarkable - spanned a century of tumult and dramatic change.\n\nGrenville has also written or co-written several books about the writing process which are widely used in creative writing workshops and in schools and universities: ''The Writing Book'', ''Writing from Start to Finish'', and ''Making Stories'' (co-written with [[Sue Woolfe]]).\n\nGrenville has been awarded fellowships from the International Association of University Women and from the Literary Arts Board of the [[Australia Council]].<ref name = \"Whitlock2\"/> Her novels have all been published in the UK and US as well as Australia and have been translated into many languages, including German, Swedish, French, Hebrew and Chinese.\n\n==Style and subject matter==\n\nGrenville's early fiction presented characters trying to free themselves from social and gender stereotypes.  ''Bearded Ladies'' is a collection of short stories about women trying to free themselves from the gender stereotypes of their society.\n\n''Lilian's Story'', set in the early 20th century, takes as its subject a woman who rejects her middle-class background and the conventional future that is expected of her, and instead chooses to live as a street person, making a living by offering recitations from [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]. At the end of her life she declares joyously: \"Drive on, George. I am ready for whatever comes next.\"\n\n''Joan Makes History'' is a satirical re-writing of Australia's history, foregrounding the women rather than the men. Joan is an Everywoman character who in various guises lives through all the iconic moments of Australia's past. She \"makes history\" both by simply living her life, and by (re)making history by writing it.\n\n''Dreamhouse'' is a black comedy about a marriage on the rocks. It explores themes of both men and women freeing themselves from stereotypes to accept their true selves. Both partners in the marriage are attracted to their own sex: the wife is prepared to acknowledge that and act on it while the husband refuses to.\n\n''The Idea of Perfection'' is about people haunted by the impossible ideal  of perfection. The two main characters are both middle-aged and frumpish, and consider themselves unlovably flawed.  The journey they make is to recognise that to be \"imperfect\" is simply to be human, and carries its own power. As the epigraph from [[Leonardo da Vinci]] asserts: \"An arch is two weaknesses that together make a strength\".\n\n''The Secret River'' is set in early 19th-century Australia and is based on the story of one of Grenville's convict ancestors, [[Solomon Wiseman]], a London boatman transported for theft.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Secret River|url=http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/events/exhibitions/2010/onehundred/100-objects/Exhibit-097.htm|work=One Hundred exhibition|publisher=State Library of NSW|accessdate=25 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207193245/http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/events/exhibitions/2010/onehundred/100-objects/Exhibit-097.htm|archive-date=7 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> She takes that story as a means of exploring a wider theme: the dark legacy of [[colonialism]], especially its impact on Australia's Aboriginal peoples. The title comes from the anthropologist [[William Edward Hanley Stanner|W. E. H. Stanner]], who wrote about a \"secret river of blood flowing through Australia's history\": the story of white Australia's relationship with the Aboriginal people.\n\nGrenville has written a memoir of the research and writing of ''The Secret River'', entitled ''Searching for the Secret River''.\n\n''The Lieutenant'' is the story of one of the very earliest moments of black-white relationship in Australia, at the time of first settlement in 1788. Based on a historical source \u2013 the [[Gadigal]]-language notebooks of Lieutenant [[William Dawes (Royal Marines officer)|William Dawes]] \u2013 the novel tells the story of a unique friendship. In learning the Gadigal language from a young girl, Dawes wrote down word-for-word parts of their conversations. Grenville has used these fragments as the basis for a novel exploring how it might be possible for two people to reach across the gulfs of language and culture that separate them, and arrive at a relationship of mutual warmth and respect. She has described it as a \"mirror-image\" of ''The Secret River.''\n\n''Sarah Thornhill'' is a sequel to ''The Secret River''.  It tells the story of one of the children of the main character in the earlier book. Sarah Thornhill grows up knowing nothing of the dark secret in her family's past, and when she has to confront it, the direction of her life and her thinking is changed.  It's a story about secrets and lies, and how to deal with a dark legacy from the past. Grenville has said that the book is set in the 19th century, but is as much about the ugly secrets in Australian history that her own generation inherited.\n\nThese three books form a loose trilogy \u2013 \"The Colonial Trilogy\" \u2013 about the first three generations of white settlement in Australia, and what that shared black/white history means for contemporary Australians.  The themes of the three books reach beyond Australia: all are widely read in other countries where colonialism has left a problematic legacy.\n\nGrenville frequently does extensive research for her novels, often using historical or other sources as the starting-point for the work of the imagination. She says of her books that they are \"sometimes inspired by historical events, but they are imaginative constructs, not an attempt to write history\".<ref name=\"PE\"/>\n\nSome years after her mother died, Grenville put together a book about her, based on the memoirs and recordings her mother left.  The result is ''One Life: My Mother's Story'', a book about a woman born in 1912 who rode the waves of tumultuous change that happened over the course of her life.\n\nGrenville's most recent non-fiction book is about the health problems that can be caused by the synthetic fragrances that are all around us: ''The Case Against Fragrance''.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* Fellow of the Australian Academy of the Humanities (FAHA) in 2008<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr Kate Grenville FAHA|url=https://www.humanities.org.au/our-fellows/fellows/?find_contact_id=3029&section_select=0&fellowType_select=0&bio_search&name_search=grenville&membership_since_search&country_search=0&state_search=0|website=Australian Academy of the Humanities|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref>\n* Honorary Doctorate of Letters from the [[University of New South Wales]]<ref name=about/> in 2010\n* Honorary Doctorate of Letters from the University of Sydney<ref name=about>{{Cite web |url = http://kategrenville.com/biography |title = About Kate Grenville |accessdate = 27 November 2014 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141225095143/http://kategrenville.com/biography |archivedate = 25 December 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> in 2012\n* Honorary Doctorate of Letters from [[Macquarie University]] in 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://mq.edu.au/newsroom/2013/04/19/celebrated-australian-writer-kate-grenville-receives-an-honorary-doctorate/|title = Celebrated Australian writer Kate Grenville receives an honorary doctorate|date = 19 April 2013|accessdate = 27 November 2014|website = |publisher = Macquarie University|last = |first = }}</ref>\n* The Dixson Medal awarded by the [[Library Council of New South Wales]] in 2014<ref>{{citation |url = http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/about/awards/library_honours/2014_library_honours_recipients.html |title = 2014 Honours of the Library Council of New South Wales |accessdate = 12 July 2015 |publisher = State Library of New South Wales |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150501171927/http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/about/awards/library_honours/2014_library_honours_recipients.html |archivedate = 1 May 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Prizes===\n* 1984 \u2013 [[The Australian/Vogel Literary Award]] for ''Lilian's Story''\n* 1995 \u2013 [[Vance Palmer Prize for Fiction|Victorian Premier's Vance Palmer Prize for Fiction]] for ''Dark Places''<ref>http://www.literaryawards.com.au/victorianpremiers.html</ref>\n* 2001 \u2013 [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] for ''[[The Idea of Perfection]]''\n* 2006 \u2013 [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]] for ''[[The Secret River]]''\n* 2006 \u2013 [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards]], Christina Stead Prize for fiction for ''The Secret River''\n* 2006 \u2013 [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards]], Community Relations Commission Award for ''The Secret River''\n\n===Shortlisted===\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[The Secret River]]'' \u2013 [[Miles Franklin Award]] and the [[Man Booker Prize]].\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Short story collections===\n*''Bearded Ladies:Stories'' (1984) {{ISBN|0-7022-1716-6}}\n\n===Novels===\n*''Lilian's Story'' (1985), {{ISBN|1-86448-284-2}}\n*''Dreamhouse'' (1986), {{ISBN|0-7022-1959-2}}\n*''Joan Makes History: A Novel'' (1988), {{ISBN|0-7022-2174-0}}\n*''Dark Places'' (1994), {{ISBN|0-330-33549-9}} (alternative title: ''Albion's Story'')\n*''[[The Idea of Perfection]]'' (1999)\n*''[[The Secret River]]'' (2005)\n*''[[The Lieutenant (novel)|The Lieutenant]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Sarah Thornhill]]'', sequel to ''The Secret River'', (2011)\n*''A Room Made of Leaves'' (2020)<ref>[https://www.goodreadingmagazine.com.au/latestnews/kate-grenville-new-2020.html \"Kate Grenville releasing new book, A Room Made of Leaves, in 2020\"], ''Good Reading''.</ref>\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''The Writing Book: A Manual for Fiction Writers'' (1990), {{ISBN|0-04-442124-9}}\n*''Making Stories: How Ten Australian Novels Were Written'' (1993), with Woolfe, Sue {{ISBN|1-86373-316-7}}\n*''Writing from Start to Finish: a Six-Step Guide'' (2001)\n*''Searching for the Secret River'' (2006), {{ISBN|1-921145-39-0}}\n*''One Life: My Mother's Story'' (2015), {{ISBN|978-1-922182-05-0}}\n*''The Case Against Fragrance'' (2017), {{ISBN|978-1-925355-95-6}}.\n\n===Translations===\nGrenville's work has appeared in: Swedish, Dutch, German, French, Italian, Czech, Bulgarian, Spanish, Portuguese, Hebrew, Norwegian, Greek,  Mandarin and Japanese.<!--unsure why this list is here in such a vague way: which books appeared in which languages? Better added in the lists above.-->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*Henderson, Gerard (2008), [http://www.smh.com.au/news/obituaries/a-career-upon-lifes-pendulum/2008/03/18/1205602379769.html?page=fullpage \"A career upon life's pendulum: Ken Gee, 1915\u20132008\"] (Obituary), published in ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 2008-03-19, p.&nbsp;22 \n*Whitlock, Gillian (ed.) (1989), ''Eight Voices of the Eighties: Stories, Journalism and Criticism by Australian Women Writers'', St Lucia, University of Queensland Press\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071011071248/http://www.allenandunwin.com/default.aspx?page=311&author=212 Kate Grenville] \u2013 [[Allen and Unwin]] Book Publishers\n*[http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/podcasts/worldservice/wbc/rss.xml Podcast of Kate Grenville discussing ''The Secret River''] on the BBC's ''[[World Book Club]]''\n* VIDEO: [http://www.abc.net.au/tv/fora/stories/2009/07/09/2621185.htm Kate Grenville at the Melbourne Festival of Ideas, talking about Artists, Writers and Climate Change] on [http://www.abc.net.au/tv/fora/default.htm ABC Fora]\n*[http://www.abc.net.au/rn/bookshow/stories/2008/2375252.htm Transcript of interview] with [[Ramona Koval]], ''[[The Book Show]]'', [[ABC Radio National]], 1 October 2008.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120205072028/http://cousincreep.com/ivfiles/Kate_Grenville_Interview.mp3 MP3 of Interview with Kate Grenville speaking about her book ''The Idea of Perfection'' from Radio 3RRR]\n*[http://www.austlit.edu.au/run?ex=ShowAgent&agentId=A%28pO AustLit Resource Author Entry.]\n*[http://www.canongate.net/Kate-Grenville Kate Grenville's site by Canongate]\n* {{British council|id=kate-grenville|name=Kate Grenville}}\n*[http://www.cbc.ca/wordsatlarge/features/feature.php?storyId=158 Online interview from CBC ''Words at Large'']\n\n{{Commonwealth Writers' Prize - Best Book Winners}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grenville, Kate}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian feminist writers]]\n[[Category:Australian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Australian women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women writers]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image = Kate Grenville. Danielle Bagnato. Text Publishing.jpg\n| name        = Kate Grenville\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AO}}\n| caption     = Grenville in Melbourne, 2017\n| pseudonym   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth-date and age|14 October 1950}}\n| birth_place = [[Sydney, Australia]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Novelist, teacher of creative writing\n| nationality = Australian \n| period      = \n| genre       = General fiction, historical fiction, short stories\n| subject     = \n| movement    = \n| debut_works = \n| signature   = \n| website = {{url|http://kategrenville.com.au}}\n}}\n\n'''Catherine Elizabeth Grenville''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AO}} (born 14 October 1950) is an Australian author. She has published fifteen books, including fiction, non-fiction, biography, and books about the writing process. In 2001, she won the [[Orange Prize for Fiction|Orange Prize]] for ''[[The Idea of Perfection]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Neill|first1=Rosemary|title=A prize of one's own|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/a-prize-of-ones-own/news-story/4e87f8a36c0ab40502852e8c557444e9|accessdate=13 October 2017|work=The Australian}}</ref> and in 2006 she won the [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]] for ''[[The Secret River]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Australian writer wins book prize|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4803084.stm|date=14 March 2006|accessdate=13 October 2017|publisher=BBC}}</ref> ''The Secret River'' was also shortlisted for the [[Man Booker Prize]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kate Grenville, Australian novelist|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Kate-Grenville#ref945357|website=Encyclopaedia Britannica|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nHer novels have been published worldwide and have been translated into many languages. Three have been adapted into feature films.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kate Grenville|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0340300/|website=IMDb|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> ''The Secret River'' was adapted for the stage by [[Andrew Bovell]] and toured by the [[Sydney Theatre Company]] in 2019.<ref>Sydney Theatre Company (2019), ''The Secret River'', [[Edinburgh International Festival]] theatre programme.</ref>\n\n==Life==\n\nKate Grenville was born in Sydney in 1950, one of three children born to [[Ken Gee (judge)|Kenneth Grenville Gee]], a [[District Court of New South Wales|District Court]] judge and barrister; and Isobel Russell, a pharmacist.<ref name = \"Henderson\">Henderson (2008).</ref> She was educated at [[Cremorne Girls High School]], the [[University of Sydney]] (BA Hons) and the [[University of Colorado]] (MA). After completing her undergraduate degree at the University of Sydney, Grenville worked in the film industry, mostly editing documentaries at [[Film Australia]]. She has also been a teacher of [[creative writing]]. Between 1976 and 1980 she lived in London and Paris, and wrote fiction while supporting herself by doing film-editing, writing, and secretarial jobs. In 1980 she went to the [[University of Colorado at Boulder|University of Colorado]] at [[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder]] to do a master's degree in creative writing. She returned to Australia in 1983<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.users.bigpond.com/kgrenville/bio.html |title=Kate Grenville - My Life - a biographical note |accessdate=14 May 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501165305/http://www.users.bigpond.com/kgrenville/bio.html |archivedate= 1 May 2008 }}</ref> and became a sub-editor at [[SBS Television]] in the [[subtitle (captioning)|subtitling]] department. She won a literary grant in 1986 and left SBS to pursue her writing.<ref>Waldren, M. (2001), [http://members.optusnet.com.au/~waldrenm/kate.html \"Kismet Kate: An Interview with the Winner of the Orange Prize for Fiction 2001\"]. Retrieved 19 May 2007.</ref> Since the early 1990s she has been an Honorary Associate at the [[University of Sydney]].<ref>[http://www.usyd.edu.au/news/84.html?newsstoryid=1342 \"And now the Booker: Grenville's accolades keep coming\"], University of Sydney, 26 September 2006. Retrieved 2 August 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2006 she was awarded a Doctorate of Creative Arts by the [[University of Technology, Sydney]]<ref name=\"PE\">Peter Ellis, Interview with Kate Grenville, 1 August 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.newsroom.uts.edu.au/news/detail.cfm?ItemId=7032 \"Searching for the secret river\"], 6 December 2006. Retrieved 2 August 2009.</ref> under the supervision of [[Glenda Adams]] and Paula Hamilton. She has also been awarded an Honorary Doctorate of Letters from the University of Sydney,<ref>{{cite news|title=Outstanding individuals recognised in honorary degrees|url=http://sydney.edu.au/news/84.html?newsstoryid=10490|date=9 November 2012|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=University of Sydney}}</ref> the [[University of New South Wales|University of NSW]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Kate Grenville's letters|url=https://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/newsroom/articles/kate-grenvilles-letters/|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=University of New South Wales}}</ref> and [[Macquarie University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Celebrated Australian writer Kate Grenville receives an Honorary Degree|url=http://www.mq.edu.au/newsroom/2013/04/19/celebrated-australian-writer-kate-grenville-receives-an-honorary-doctorate/|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=Macquarie University}}</ref>\n\nGrenville has been married to Robert Steiner and cartoonist [[Bruce Petty]]. She lives in Sydney with her son and daughter. Her leisure activities include learning to play the cello<ref name=\"bio\"/> and performing in an amateur orchestra.\n\n==Career==\n\nKate Grenville's reputation as a short story writer was made by the publication in 1984 of her collection ''[[Bearded Ladies]]''.<ref name = \"Whitlock2\">Whitlock (1989), p. 2.</ref> On its publication, [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] wrote \"Here is someone who can really write\".{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n''[[Lilian's Story]]'' was her first published novel (1985) and won [[The Australian/Vogel Literary Award]]. It was loosely based on the story of [[Bea Miles]], known in Sydney for her eccentric public behaviour.<ref>{{cite web | first=Kate | last=Grenville | title =The Novelist as Barbarian | publisher =[[National Library of Australia]] | url =http://www.nla.gov.au/events/history/papers/Kate_Grenville%20.html | accessdate = 2015-07-12}}</ref> It has become one of Australia's best-loved novels and in 1996 was made into a film starring [[Ruth Cracknell]] and [[Toni Collette]]; Collette won the [[Australian Film Institute]] [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|award for supporting actress]] for her performance as the young Lilian.\n\n''[[Dreamhouse (novel)|Dreamhouse]]'' followed in 1986, and appeared as the 1994 film ''[[Traps (1994 film)|Traps]]''. ''[[Joan Makes History]]'' \u2013 the recipient of an Australian Bicentennial Commission \u2013 was published in 1988.\n\nIn 1994 Grenville returned to the characters and setting of ''Lilian's Story'' with a companion novel \u2013 ''[[Dark Places (Grenville novel)|Dark Places]]'' \u2013 that re-tells the events of the earlier novel from the point of view of Lilian's incestuous father. ''Dark Places'' won the [[Victorian Premier's Literary Award]] in 1995. (In the US this novel is titled ''Albion's Story''.)\n\n''[[The Idea of Perfection]]'' appeared in 2000 and won the Orange Prize for Fiction, at the time Britain's richest literary award.\n\nIn 2006 ''[[The Secret River]]'' was published, the first of Grenville's books that take Australia's colonial past, and relations with Australia's indigenous people, as their subject. ''The Secret River'' was inspired by the story of Grenville's own great-great-great grandfather, a [[Convicts in Australia|convict]] sent to Australia from London in 1806.  This book won the Commonwealth Prize,<ref>Richard Lea, [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/may/08/news.awardsandprizes \"Kate Grenville to meet the Queen\"], ''The Guardian'', 8 May 2006.</ref> the [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards#Christina Stead Prize for Fiction|Christina Stead Award]], and the [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards#Community Relations Commission Award|NSW Premier's Community Relations Prize]], and was shortlisted for the [[Man Booker Prize]].\n\n''Searching for The Secret River'' (2006) is a memoir about the research and writing of the novel, tracing the journey of the author's increasing awareness of how Australia's colonial past informs its present.\n\n''[[The Lieutenant (novel)|The Lieutenant]]'' (2008) is set thirty years earlier than ''The Secret River''. Based on the historical notebooks of Lieutenant [[William Dawes (British Marines officer)|William Dawes]], it tells the story of the friendship between a soldier with the [[First Fleet]] and a young [[Gadigal]] girl.  These two novels together explore something of the complexity of black-white relations in Australia's past.\n\n''[[Sarah Thornhill]]'' (2011) is the sequel to ''The Secret River'' and takes up the story of William Thornhill's youngest daughter. It can be read as a stand-alone novel, without reference to ''The Secret River''.\n\nHer latest book is ''One Life: My Mother's Story'', in which Grenville uses the fragments of memoir that her mother left to construct the story of a woman whose life - in some ways typical of her times, in other ways remarkable - spanned a century of tumult and dramatic change.\n\nGrenville has also written or co-written several books about the writing process which are widely used in creative writing workshops and in schools and universities: ''The Writing Book'', ''Writing from Start to Finish'', and ''Making Stories'' (co-written with [[Sue Woolfe]]).\n\nGrenville has been awarded fellowships from the International Association of University Women and from the Literary Arts Board of the [[Australia Council]].<ref name = \"Whitlock2\"/> Her novels have all been published in the UK and US as well as Australia and have been translated into many languages, including German, Swedish, French, Hebrew and Chinese.\n\n==Style and subject matter==\n\nGrenville's early fiction presented characters trying to free themselves from social and gender stereotypes.  ''Bearded Ladies'' is a collection of short stories about women trying to free themselves from the gender stereotypes of their society.\n\n''Lilian's Story'', set in the early 20th century, takes as its subject a woman who rejects her middle-class background and the conventional future that is expected of her, and instead chooses to live as a street person, making a living by offering recitations from [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]. At the end of her life she declares joyously: \"Drive on, George. I am ready for whatever comes next.\"\n\n''Joan Makes History'' is a satirical re-writing of Australia's history, foregrounding the women rather than the men. Joan is an Everywoman character who in various guises lives through all the iconic moments of Australia's past. She \"makes history\" both by simply living her life, and by (re)making history by writing it.\n\n''Dreamhouse'' is a black comedy about a marriage on the rocks. It explores themes of both men and women freeing themselves from stereotypes to accept their true selves. Both partners in the marriage are attracted to their own sex: the wife is prepared to acknowledge that and act on it while the husband refuses to.\n\n''The Idea of Perfection'' is about people haunted by the impossible ideal  of perfection. The two main characters are both middle-aged and frumpish, and consider themselves unlovably flawed.  The journey they make is to recognise that to be \"imperfect\" is simply to be human, and carries its own power. As the epigraph from [[Leonardo da Vinci]] asserts: \"An arch is two weaknesses that together make a strength\".\n\n''The Secret River'' is set in early 19th-century Australia and is based on the story of one of Grenville's convict ancestors, [[Solomon Wiseman]], a London boatman transported for theft.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Secret River|url=http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/events/exhibitions/2010/onehundred/100-objects/Exhibit-097.htm|work=One Hundred exhibition|publisher=State Library of NSW|accessdate=25 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207193245/http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/events/exhibitions/2010/onehundred/100-objects/Exhibit-097.htm|archive-date=7 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> She takes that story as a means of exploring a wider theme: the dark legacy of [[colonialism]], especially its impact on Australia's Aboriginal peoples. The title comes from the anthropologist [[William Edward Hanley Stanner|W. E. H. Stanner]], who wrote about a \"secret river of blood flowing through Australia's history\": the story of white Australia's relationship with the Aboriginal people.\n\nGrenville has written a memoir of the research and writing of ''The Secret River'', entitled ''Searching for the Secret River''.\n\n''The Lieutenant'' is the story of one of the very earliest moments of black-white relationship in Australia, at the time of first settlement in 1788. Based on a historical source \u2013 the [[Gadigal]]-language notebooks of Lieutenant [[William Dawes (Royal Marines officer)|William Dawes]] \u2013 the novel tells the story of a unique friendship. In learning the Gadigal language from a young girl, Dawes wrote down word-for-word parts of their conversations. Grenville has used these fragments as the basis for a novel exploring how it might be possible for two people to reach across the gulfs of language and culture that separate them, and arrive at a relationship of mutual warmth and respect. She has described it as a \"mirror-image\" of ''The Secret River.''\n\n''Sarah Thornhill'' is a sequel to ''The Secret River''.  It tells the story of one of the children of the main character in the earlier book. Sarah Thornhill grows up knowing nothing of the dark secret in her family's past, and when she has to confront it, the direction of her life and her thinking is changed.  It's a story about secrets and lies, and how to deal with a dark legacy from the past. Grenville has said that the book is set in the 19th century, but is as much about the ugly secrets in Australian history that her own generation inherited.\n\nThese three books form a loose trilogy \u2013 \"The Colonial Trilogy\" \u2013 about the first three generations of white settlement in Australia, and what that shared black/white history means for contemporary Australians.  The themes of the three books reach beyond Australia: all are widely read in other countries where colonialism has left a problematic legacy.\n\nGrenville frequently does extensive research for her novels, often using historical or other sources as the starting-point for the work of the imagination. She says of her books that they are \"sometimes inspired by historical events, but they are imaginative constructs, not an attempt to write history\".<ref name=\"PE\"/>\n\nSome years after her mother died, Grenville put together a book about her, based on the memoirs and recordings her mother left.  The result is ''One Life: My Mother's Story'', a book about a woman born in 1912 who rode the waves of tumultuous change that happened over the course of her life.\n\nGrenville's most recent non-fiction book is about the health problems that can be caused by the synthetic fragrances that are all around us: ''The Case Against Fragrance''.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* Fellow of the Australian Academy of the Humanities (FAHA) in 2008<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr Kate Grenville FAHA|url=https://www.humanities.org.au/our-fellows/fellows/?find_contact_id=3029&section_select=0&fellowType_select=0&bio_search&name_search=grenville&membership_since_search&country_search=0&state_search=0|website=Australian Academy of the Humanities|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref>\n* Honorary Doctorate of Letters from the [[University of New South Wales]]<ref name=about/> in 2010\n* Honorary Doctorate of Letters from the University of Sydney<ref name=about>{{Cite web |url = http://kategrenville.com/biography |title = About Kate Grenville |accessdate = 27 November 2014 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141225095143/http://kategrenville.com/biography |archivedate = 25 December 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> in 2012\n* Honorary Doctorate of Letters from [[Macquarie University]] in 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://mq.edu.au/newsroom/2013/04/19/celebrated-australian-writer-kate-grenville-receives-an-honorary-doctorate/|title = Celebrated Australian writer Kate Grenville receives an honorary doctorate|date = 19 April 2013|accessdate = 27 November 2014|website = |publisher = Macquarie University|last = |first = }}</ref>\n* The Dixson Medal awarded by the [[Library Council of New South Wales]] in 2014<ref>{{citation |url = http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/about/awards/library_honours/2014_library_honours_recipients.html |title = 2014 Honours of the Library Council of New South Wales |accessdate = 12 July 2015 |publisher = State Library of New South Wales |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150501171927/http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/about/awards/library_honours/2014_library_honours_recipients.html |archivedate = 1 May 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Prizes===\n* 1984 \u2013 [[The Australian/Vogel Literary Award]] for ''Lilian's Story''\n* 1995 \u2013 [[Vance Palmer Prize for Fiction|Victorian Premier's Vance Palmer Prize for Fiction]] for ''Dark Places''<ref>http://www.literaryawards.com.au/victorianpremiers.html</ref>\n* 2001 \u2013 [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] for ''[[The Idea of Perfection]]''\n* 2006 \u2013 [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]] for ''[[The Secret River]]''\n* 2006 \u2013 [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards]], Christina Stead Prize for fiction for ''The Secret River''\n* 2006 \u2013 [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards]], Community Relations Commission Award for ''The Secret River''\n\n===Shortlisted===\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[The Secret River]]'' \u2013 [[Miles Franklin Award]] and the [[Man Booker Prize]].\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Short story collections===\n*''Bearded Ladies:Stories'' (1984) {{ISBN|0-7022-1716-6}}\n\n===Novels===\n*''Lilian's Story'' (1985), {{ISBN|1-86448-284-2}}\n*''Dreamhouse'' (1986), {{ISBN|0-7022-1959-2}}\n*''Joan Makes History: A Novel'' (1988), {{ISBN|0-7022-2174-0}}\n*''Dark Places'' (1994), {{ISBN|0-330-33549-9}} (alternative title: ''Albion's Story'')\n*''[[The Idea of Perfection]]'' (1999)\n*''[[The Secret River]]'' (2005)\n*''[[The Lieutenant (novel)|The Lieutenant]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Sarah Thornhill]]'', sequel to ''The Secret River'', (2011)\n*''A Room Made of Leaves'' (2020)<ref>[https://www.goodreadingmagazine.com.au/latestnews/kate-grenville-new-2020.html \"Kate Grenville releasing new book, A Room Made of Leaves, in 2020\"], ''Good Reading''.</ref>\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''The Writing Book: A Manual for Fiction Writers'' (1990), {{ISBN|0-04-442124-9}}\n*''Making Stories: How Ten Australian Novels Were Written'' (1993), with Woolfe, Sue {{ISBN|1-86373-316-7}}\n*''Writing from Start to Finish: a Six-Step Guide'' (2001)\n*''Searching for the Secret River'' (2006), {{ISBN|1-921145-39-0}}\n*''One Life: My Mother's Story'' (2015), {{ISBN|978-1-922182-05-0}}\n*''The Case Against Fragrance'' (2017), {{ISBN|978-1-925355-95-6}}.\n\n===Translations===\nGrenville's work has appeared in: Swedish, Dutch, German, French, Italian, Czech, Bulgarian, Spanish, Portuguese, Hebrew, Norwegian, Greek,  Mandarin and Japanese.<!--unsure why this list is here in such a vague way: which books appeared in which languages? Better added in the lists above.-->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*Henderson, Gerard (2008), [http://www.smh.com.au/news/obituaries/a-career-upon-lifes-pendulum/2008/03/18/1205602379769.html?page=fullpage \"A career upon life's pendulum: Ken Gee, 1915\u20132008\"] (Obituary), published in ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 2008-03-19, p.&nbsp;22 \n*Whitlock, Gillian (ed.) (1989), ''Eight Voices of the Eighties: Stories, Journalism and Criticism by Australian Women Writers'', St Lucia, University of Queensland Press\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071011071248/http://www.allenandunwin.com/default.aspx?page=311&author=212 Kate Grenville] \u2013 [[Allen and Unwin]] Book Publishers\n*[http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/podcasts/worldservice/wbc/rss.xml Podcast of Kate Grenville discussing ''The Secret River''] on the BBC's ''[[World Book Club]]''\n* VIDEO: [http://www.abc.net.au/tv/fora/stories/2009/07/09/2621185.htm Kate Grenville at the Melbourne Festival of Ideas, talking about Artists, Writers and Climate Change] on [http://www.abc.net.au/tv/fora/default.htm ABC Fora]\n*[http://www.abc.net.au/rn/bookshow/stories/2008/2375252.htm Transcript of interview] with [[Ramona Koval]], ''[[The Book Show]]'', [[ABC Radio Nat